<HEADLINE> Chinese Ambassador to UNOG Presents Credentials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 14 (Xinhua) -- China's new permanent
representative to the United Nations and other international
organizations at Geneva, Qiao Zonghuai, presented his credentials
here Monday to Vladimir Petrovsky, director-general of the United
Nations Office at Geneva (UNOG).
</P>
<P>
From 1997 until his assignment to Geneva, Qiao was ambassador
extraordinary and plenipotentiary of China to Sweden. He served as
ambassador extraordinary and plenipotentiary of China to the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea from 1993 to 1997, and to
Finland from 1991 to 1993. Qiao also held the same post
concurrently to Estonia from 1991 to 1992.
</P>
<P>
Prior to his diplomatic postings, Qiao was
deputy-secretary-general of Xinhua News Agency, Hong Kong branch,
from 1984 to 1987, then was deputy director of the agency in Hong
Kong from 1987 to 1991.
</P>
<P>
Born in July 1944 in the eastern Chinese province of Jiangsu,
Qiao was a visiting scholar at the Chinese University of Hong Kong
from 1983 to 1984, and was an assistant research fellow at the
Institute of Space Medical-Engineering (ISME), the Commission of
Science, Technology and Industry for National Defense of China
from 1981 to 1983.
</P>
<P>
Qiao was a research intern at the ISME from 1968 to 1978, and
was a graduate student of engineering thermophysics at the
Institute of Mechanics of the Chinese Academy of Sciences from
1978 to 1981. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
