<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Leaders Decide to Admit Cambodia at Date to Be Decided </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) have agreed to admit Cambodia into
the regional grouping without setting the specific date for the
admission.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN heads of state and government "decided to admit
Cambodia into the ASEAN as the 10th member," Vietnamese Foreign
Minister Nguyen Manh Cam told reporters after leaders from the
nine ASEAN countries held consultations here Monday night.
</P>
<P>
However, Cam did not give the time when Cambodia will actually
become an ASEAN member, saying only that ASEAN foreign ministers
will organize a special admission ceremony in Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
Attending the consultations were Brunei Sultan Haji Hassanal
Bolkiah, Indonesian President B.J. Habibie, Lao Prime Minister
Sisavat Keobounphan, Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad,
Myanmar Prime Minister Than Shwe, Philippine President Joseph
Estrada, Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong, Thai Prime
Minister Chuan Leekpai and Vietnamese Prime Minister Phan Van
Khai.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Prime Minister Khai said the ASEAN foreign ministers
will make arrangements "as early as possible."
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan of Thailand, which urged a
delay in Cambodia's admission, also told reporters that "the time
has not been decided yet."
</P>
<P>
The consultations, a last-minute effort for Cambodia to join
the ASEAN in time for the Sixth ASEAN Summit to be held Tuesday
and Wednesday, came after ASEAN foreign ministers failed to reach
consensus on the matter at their meetings last week as the member
countries were divided over Cambodia's accession.
</P>
<P>
Host country Vietnam and some other countries favored
Cambodia's immediate admission while others such as Thailand and
Singapore asked for a delay until the political situation is more
stable in the country.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN had decided to admit Cambodia together with Laos and
Myanmar in July last year, but the admission was deferred after
armed conflicts broke out between the forces of the then First
Prime Minister Norodom Ranariddh and Second Prime Minister Hun
Sen, resulting in Ranariddh's ouster.
</P>
<P>
The countries favoring Cambodia's admission argue that a
coalition government was already established in the country in
November, with Hun Sen as the sole prime minister, and the United
Nations restored the country's seat earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
However, Singapore and Thailand would like to wait for more
time, saying the conditions set for Cambodia's accession have not
been fully satisfied yet, including the amendment of the Cambodian
Constitution and appointment of senators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
