<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Should be Encouraged by Irish Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus should be encouraged by
the peace agreement on Northern Ireland, said Desmond O'Malley,
chairman of the Joint Committee on Foreign Affairs of the Irish
Parliament here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
O'Malley, who was heading an Irish parliament delegation, said
after meeting with Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides that the Good
Friday agreement signed in April and the difficulties in its
implementation were part of their discussions.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which will end the 30-year-long bloody conflict
in the divided British province, preserves Northern Ireland's
links with Britain while building its closer ties with Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Drawing "some parallels" between the solution of the Northern
Ireland problem and the one in Cyprus itself, O'Malley said this
"should be a source of encouragement to everyone on this island
that what did appear intractable in Northern Ireland only a few
years ago has now actually been solved by the political will and
with the assistance of the European Union (EU) and the U.S."
</P>
<P>
O'Malley also expressed full support for Cyprus' bid for full
membership of the EU, saying that Cyprus should not be excluded
from the group because of the political problem on the island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since Turkey
landed its troops and took over the northern third of the island
in 1974 following a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
O'Malley said that "Ireland like other small states in the
E.U. is anxious that a country like Cyprus which is fully in the
European tradition would be able to join as a full member."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus along with Slovenia, Estonia, Hungary, Poland and the
Czech Republic started substantive accession negotiations with the
EU last month.
</P>
<P>
O'Malley and his delegation concluded a six-day visit to Cyprus
on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
