<HEADLINE> Romanian Bank for Development Sold 51 Pct Stake to France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 14 (Xinhua) - A 51 percent stake by the
Romanian Bank for Development (BRD) is sold to the French group
Societe Generale for 200 million U.S. dollars, as official
document was signed here Monday.
</P>
<P>
This is one of the most important privatizations in the last
nine years in the country.
</P>
<P>
The document was signed by Radu Sarbu, president of Romania's
chief privatization body -- the State Ownership Fund, and Philippe
Citerne, the first deputy-president of Societe Generale. Romanian
Prime Minister Radu Vasile and Governor of the National Bank Mugur
Isarescu attended the event.
</P>
<P>
Around 8 percent of Romania's foreign trade is currently
operated through the BRD, experts said. By unitary policies of
maintaining and attracting customers, and by adapting permanently
to the market's conditions, the bank will operate 12 percent-15
percent of the country's foreign trade within the next three
years, they said.
</P>
<P>
The infrastructure by the BRD includes 165 units, out of which
106 are new or modernized outlets. At the same time, the bank has
set up and developed an adequate database system. In 1999, the
bank will be financed through an entire computerized system.
</P>
<P>
The Banker magazine of the United Kingdom this autumn ranked
the BRD the 315th among the biggest 500 commercial banks around
Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
