<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Faces Challenges of Peace, Economic Crisis in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 14 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said Monday that the United Nations faces challenges of
international peace and security and economic and social crisis in
the coming new year.
</P>
<P>
Annan told a press conference, "In the coming year we face a
double challenge. There is perennial challenge of international
peace and security. And there is the challenge of economic and
social crisis, which really means the challenge of globalization
and global governance."
</P>
<P>
None of the crisis in Africa, the Balkans, Afghanistan and Iraq
has been resolved, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The best we can say is that in Kosovo, and in Iraq, all-out
war has been avoided for the time being," he said. "But unless
people abide by their commitments, and unless they redouble their
efforts to find peaceful solutions, we have every reason to fear
the worst in 1999."
</P>
<P>
"These crises take up an enormous amount of the organization's
time," he said. "It might be tempting to leave the economic and
social issues to others. But I am convinced we cannot afford to do
that."
</P>
<P>
The connection between the two challenges is too clear, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Unless we tackle the underlying distortions and imbalances in
the global economy -- unless we start to provide the kind of
`global governance' which is needed -- we must expect more
conflicts and even more intractable ones," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Economic and political security are, and always have been,
closely interconnected," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief told his end-of-year press conference that
"incredibly enough, this year -- my second as secretary-general --
has gone even faster than the first. I suppose it has been even
more eventful."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Annan listed "some more welcome events" in the
outgoing year, which "were the fruit of strenuous efforts over a
long period," he said.
</P>
<P>
They were the agreement on the Statute of the International
Criminal Court, the entry-into-force of the Ottawa landmine ban,
the elections and formation of a new coalition government in
Cambodia -- which has just resumed its seat in the General
Assembly, and the celebration of the 50th anniversary of the
Universal Declaration of Human Rights, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
