<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full-Scale Civil War May Break Out: Angolan FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Foreign Minister
Venancio da Silva Moura said Monday that the Angolan peace
process is at a crucial point and a full-scale civil war may
break out at any moment.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the ambassadors to the southern African from China,
France, Britain and from the observer states, namely, the United
States, Russia and Portugal on the fierce fighting between the
government troops and the rebel UNITA forces, Mura said that it
was the rebels who first launched the attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan foreign minister lashed some foreign reports by
saying that the Angolan government troops had only taken
defensive measures and did not attack.
</P>
<P>
Mura noted that the UNITA troops were equipped with dozens of
tanks, various kinds of missiles and long-range artillery. This
has proven once again that they did not disarm and deceived the
United Nations and the international community, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the minister pointed out that the resolution of
imposing sanctions upon the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) adopted by the U.N. Security
Council has not been implemented properly and some countries are
still providing weapons and financial assistances to the rebel
group.
</P>
<P>
Mura finally stressed that a full-scale civil war may break
out again and the Angola peace process would end in failure
unless the U.N. firmly insists on its stance against the UNITA's
war policy.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. special representative to Angola Issa Diallo also
called upon the international community here Monday to take
emergent actions to seek ways to normalize the situation in
Angola.
</P>
<P>
"The developments are going against peace. So the
international community needs to take actions as quickly as
possible," said Diallo.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government Sunday admitted for the first time that
the government forces have been engaged in fierce fighting with
UNITA forces. It blamed the United Nations and international
community for the worsening situation.
</P>
<P>
Joao Batisata De Matos, Chief of General Staff of the Angolan
army, said that what the government forces are doing is a
response to the actions taken by the rebel troops, the Angolan
News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The deteriorating situation in the country, the chief of
general staff said, is a result of the passive stance of the
United Nations over UNITA's refusal to implement the Lusaka Peace
Protocol.
</P>
<P>
He said that the international community has been condemning
the government forces for its large-scale military presence in
central part of the country, while the UNITA forces are
conducting massive military build-up there.
</P>
<P>
De Matos stressed that the government forces are capable of
controlling the situation and accomplish its task of safeguarding
the Lusaka Peace Protocol.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Revoke Anti-Israeli Clauses in Charter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA CITY, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinians took a
decisive step Monday as hundreds of Palestine National Council
(PNC) members stood with their hands raised to reaffirm the
annulment of anti-Israel provisions in their national charter.
</P>
<P>
Visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton, while addressing the
meeting, praised the PNC for doing "a remarkable thing." The
Israeli government was quick to express acceptance of the PNC move.
</P>
<P>
This paved the way for a three-way summit between Clinton,
Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat and Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu later Monday. The summit will
possibly be held at the Erez border crossing between Israel and
the Palestinian self-rule Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Almost all PNC members stood up and raised their hands to
reaffirm the revocation of provisions calling for Israel's
destruction. This was a magnificent show of Palestinian support
for the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"You raised your hands, you stood up high," Clinton said. "By
doing this, you stand up not only against what is wrong, but also
for what is right."
</P>
<P>
"Your decision touches the people of Israel" on the street, he
said, which was followed by a long applause by the PNC members.
</P>
<P>
This also puts an end to the prolonged dispute over the charter
issue between Israel and the Palestinians. Netanyahu had insisted
that the PNC vote to ratify the annulment of the articles calling
for the elimination of the "Zionist regime" in the covenant, the
de facto Palestinian constitution drafted in 1964.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's visit to Gaza, the first by a sitting U.S. president
to areas under Palestinian autonomy, gives a boost to the morale
of the Palestinians and is seen as a recognition of their
aspiration for an independent state.
</P>
<P>
Talking with Arafat at a luncheon earlier, Clinton said "for
the first time in the history of the Palestinian movement, the
Palestinian people and their elected representatives now have a
chance to determine their own destiny on their own land."
</P>
<P>
Clinton's presence at the PNC meeting was the centerpiece of
his three-day visit to Israel and the Palestinian areas, which
started Sunday, and a key element in the implementation of the
recent land-for-security deal signed by Arafat and Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's spokesman said the Israeli government has accepted
the way PNC revised the charter. The Israeli government had linked
a three-way summit with the outcome of the PNC meeting.
</P>
<P>
Israeli President Ezer Weizman congratulated Arafat on the PNC
decision and Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai described it as a
"positive step."
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Arafat stressed that the Palestinians are
committed to peace but the continued settlement activities and
the refusal to release Palestinian prisoners by Israel have
eroded mutual trust, which he said is the basis for peace.
</P>
<P>
He said the principle of land-for-peace is the basis not only
for the peace-making between Israel and the Palestinians, but also
for a solution to the conflict between Israeli and Syria and
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that five years after the historic Oslo accords
were signed, many benefits of the peace agreement remain remote
for many Palestinians. However, he stressed that the PNC decision
has showed the Palestinian commitments to peace and would help
advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He called on Israel and the Palestinians to eliminate mistrust
and hatred, and to move beyond the current situation, in which he
said there were a lot of "mistrust, misunderstanding and
mis-steps."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu put the recent peace deal on hold last week amid
violent clashes in the West Bank sparked by Israel's refusal to
release Palestinian political prisoners and what he said was
Arafat's unilateral statement on the declaration of a Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
While demanding the PNC take a formal vote on revising the
charter, Netanyahu has said that such a move alone would not be
enough to end the redeployment freeze.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with local TV after the PNC meeting, senior
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat urged Netanyahu not to look for
excuse to avoid the implementation of the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Israel has carried out the first of three withdrawals in line
with the agreement last month. The second stage of Israeli troop
redeployment is due to start this weekend.
</P>
<P>
The PNC had voted in April 1996 to revoke the anti-Israel
clauses in the Palestinian charter and the former Israeli Labor
government had accepted the vote.
</P>
<P>
But when Netanyahu came to power one month later, he said the
PNC vote was not complete and demanded the PNC convene again.
</P>
<P>
In advance of Monday's 600-member PNC vote, the Palestinian
Central Council, a smaller leadership body with 124 members, voted
overwhelmingly last Thursday to reaffirm an Arafat letter to
Clinton early this year declaring that all the anti-Israeli
clauses of the charter were revoked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
