<HEADLINE> UNDP to Launch New Recovery Initiatives in C.America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 14 (Xinhua) -- James Speth,
administrator of the United Nations Development Program (UNDP), is
in Honduras Monday as part of a three-day visit to
hurricane-damaged communities in Central America, according to the
UNDP.
</P>
<P>
Speth arrived in Honduras Sunday to inspect emergency clean-up
operations supported by the UNDP on the northern coast. He will
sign two projects in support of rehabilitation and recovery
efforts in the country.
</P>
<P>
The first 26 million U.S. dollars will help civil society
organizations reconstruct homes and schools, provide access to
credit for micro-enterprises, and reduce the risk of the epidemics
and contagious diseases. The project will also support soil
conservation and environmental education.
</P>
<P>
The second project, budgeted at 3 million U.S. dollars, will
help strengthen the newly created Special Cabinet for National
Reconstruction, which will coordinate the reconstruction and
recovery efforts in Honduras.
</P>
<P>
Speth will be in Nicaragua Tuesday where he will tour areas hit
by the disaster. Plans are being made for Speth to sign project
documents for the resettlement of displaced persons and the
integration of environmental aspects into the recovery, renovation
and transformation process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
