<HEADLINE> Egypt to Launch Second Satellite Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will put its second
communications satellite, NileSat 102, into orbit in 1999, said
Egyptian Information Minister Safwat el-Sherif Monday.
</P>
<P>
A contract will be signed before the end of this year for the
manufacture and launching of the satellite, Egypt's Middle East
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The satellite will carry 12 space channels transmitting 84
digital television channels to Africa, the Middle East and
southern Europe, said the news agency.
</P>
<P>
The satellite will be basically devoted to the African
continent in an effort to boost joint cooperation in the media
field, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
It will be made with new technology which allows mixing and
compressing channels on the satellite instead of being operated by
ground control center, he said.
</P>
<P>
The satellite will be developed by the French Matra Markoni
company in about 12 months and launched by an Ariane rocket at the
French Korou Space Center in South America, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
NileSat 101, launched in April, has 50 general and specialized
television channels with a presumed life span of 16 years.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has signed contracts with a number of Arab and African
countries to lease its space channels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
