<HEADLINE> Lebanese President Pledges Freedom of Expression </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Emile
Lahoud pledged on Monday to protect freedom of speech and press in
the country under his six-year term of office.
</P>
<P>
"The most important thing in Lebanon is that people can talk
what they think and you are the representatives of them," Lahoud
told a delegation of Lebanon's Journalists Association.
</P>
<P>
The freedom of expression is sacred and should be protected by
action rather than meer words, he said.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud stressed that anyone should enjoy his freedom within the
framework of laws and must not contradict the constitutions.
</P>
<P>
He added that he would never allow anyone to place himself
above the laws under the pretext of freedom, which will undermine
peace, social and economic stability in the country.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud, a veteran army commander, was elected as Lebanon's 11th
president in October with the strong backing of Syria who has
40,000 troops in Lebanon as peacekeepers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
