<HEADLINE> Primakov: Russia to Restore Investors' Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Russia needs to overcome the
consequences of the crisis and to create a sound legislative and
institutional basis for attracting investors, Russian Prime
Minister BBBgeny Primakov emphasized Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting of the Consultative Council for Foreign
Investments in Russia, Primakov said that favorable investment
conditions should be created for both foreign and Russian
investors because "the investment process should be based on
economic rationalism, competition and a sound legal footing."
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Primakov told a press conference that Russia
will simplify bureaucratic mechanisms, as well as customs
practices.
</P>
<P>
He said that there are plans to create "a strong state
insurance company which would insure against political threats."
</P>
<P>
On the foreign investors, Primakov said, "None of the major
foreign investors who have made direct investments in the real
sector of the economy has withdrawn from our market despite the
crisis."
</P>
<P>
"We welcome the presence of Western banks on the Russian market
and Western capital investments. We are grateful to the members of
the Consultative Council for Foreign Investments, who head major
Western companies, for not leaving us when the crisis broke out in
Russia in August," said Primakov.
</P>
<P>
The premier also stressed that the government will not
undertake "an uncontrolled emission of money" and it is launching
an uncompromising struggle against corruption and crime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
