<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan to Focus on U.N. Role in New Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 14 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said Monday that he would spend much of next year on
his report to the General Assembly, to be convened in the year
2000, on the U.N. role in the new century, but he will not focus
on the U.N. reform campaign.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference, "Much of next year will be devoted
to preparing the report on `the United Nations in the 21st
century,' which I have promised to submit to the Millennium
Assembly -- the 55th session of the General Assembly -- in the
year 2000."
</P>
<P>
As part of the preparations, the United Nations is going to
hold informal events or hearings in various regional centers,
involving member states as well as non-governmental organizations
and the private sector, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I hope these events will throw up many new and useful ideas on
the objectives of the United Nations in the decades ahead, in all
five areas of its work, peace and security, economic and social
affairs, development cooperation, humanitarian action, and of
course human rights," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, "neither the Millennium Assembly nor my report to it
will focus mainly on U.N. reform," he said. "We want to
concentrate on the long-term role and purposes of the
Organization." "But of course that presupposes that reform must
continue," he added.
</P>
<P>
Annan, the first black African to become the U.N. chief, has
championed a course of reform in the world body, including
streamlining the system, and keeping a smaller budget.
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased with what has already been achieved. I think
there is no doubt we already have a much more coherent and
purposeful system than we did two years ago," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But I am still looking for further action on such issues as
result-based budgeting, personnel management, and time limits for
new mandates," he said. "I hope 1999 will see decisive progress on
those issues."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Annan urged those countries which are in arrears
with their contributions to make "prompt payment" of their back
dues. At present, the United States is the largest owner of its
U.N. dues, and it saved its voting right in the General Assembly
next year just by paying the minimum amount of money the U.N.
Charter requires. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
