<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan on Comprehensive Review of Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 14 (Xinhua) -- It would be decided by
the Security Council of the United Nations on whether or not to
have a comprehensive review of Iraq's compliance with the U.N.
resolutions, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
At the end-of-year press conference, Annan said the council
should observe its obligations it had made in its resolutions and
lift the sanctions against Iraq once it got disarmed.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) in
charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction would
report to the council on the level of Iraq's cooperation with the
United Nations arms inspectors this week and the report would be a
fair and objective one.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that for its part, Iraq should cooperate fully and
unconditionally with the United Nations if it wanted to get the
comprehensive review.
</P>
<P>
Annan said there might be conflicts at the Security Council on
this matter because one or two countries might disagree, and that
did not mean the Security Council would not move ahead and do what
it had promised in its own resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq promised to resume full and unconditional cooperation with
the United Nations on November 14 and the Security Council
promised to conduct the comprehensive review once it cooperated
fully. Iraq expected the comprehensive review would lead to easing
or lifting of the U.N. sanctions which has been in place since
1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
