<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Summit Last Chance for Peace in DRCongo: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC) warned Monday that the African summit this week would be
"the last chance" to seek peaceful solutions to the four-month
crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
DRC Foreign Minister Jean Charles Akuto told Egypt's Middle
East News Agency that if the summit fails to reach a settlement,
force would be "the sole option" of DRC "to restore democracy" in
the central African country.
</P>
<P>
Akuto reiterated his country's readiness to negotiate with all
parties to restore security and stability in DRC.
</P>
<P>
The Organization of African Unity is scheduled to hold a summit
in Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso, Thursday and Friday on the DRC issue.
</P>
<P>
DRC government troops have been fighting since August against
rebels allegedly supported by Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
But DRC denied the existence of rebels, insisting that it is
invaded by foreign forces and calling for Rwandan and Ugandan
withdrawal from its territory.
</P>
<P>
Akuto was accompanying DRC President Laurant Kabila on a
three-day visit to Egypt. They left for home Monday.
</P>
<P>
The official termed Kabila's visit as "very successful," saying
his talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak dwelt on promotion
of bilateral relations in the fields of agriculture, trade,
industry and energy.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said Monday that Egypt and
DRC have reached three agreements, which will be signed on the
sidelines of the Ouagadougou summit.
</P>
<P>
The agreements are on preventing dual taxation, protecting
investment and enhancing trade, Moussa said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
