<HEADLINE> Angola, U.N. to Discuss Withdrawal of Observers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Minister of
Territorial Administration Faustino Muteka said Monday that his
government will discuss with the United Nations about the
withdrawal of the peacekeepers from the country.
</P>
<P>
Muteka, also head of government delegation to the joint
commission for the Angolan peace process, pointed out that "the
U.N. mission to Angola has nothing to do here now," and the Angolan
government will take up the responsibility of protecting the
people and bringing them the peace they deserve.
</P>
<P>
The minister played down the role of the blue berets, the U.N.
peacekeeping forces, in the peace process in the war-torn
southern African country.
</P>
<P>
"They (blue berets) failed to find that the UNITA did not
demilitarize its troops at all and ignored the reports by the
Angolan government," said Muteka.
</P>
<P>
He said that he had sent notes many times to the U.N.
observers mission, accusing UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi of
refusing to implement the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government Monday admitted that the government
troops recently had fierce fighting with the forces of the rebel
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) with
tanks, missiles and long-range artillery involved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
