<HEADLINE> Official Warns of Alarming Air Pollution in Tehran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Deputy Health Minister
Ali Bar Sayari on Monday warned of an "alarming" air pollution in
the Iranian capital, calling on the people to stay away from
central city.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA), Sayari
said that dangerous noxious gases have increased 10 folds in
Tehran over the past four days as a result of stable weather and
occurrence of reversion phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
He said that the inversion phenomenon which has escalated the
air pollution would continue till Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The official said the pollution has reached an alarming level
as the volume of carbon monoxide in air has increased to 18 PPM,
twice as many as the standard volume.
</P>
<P>
He warned people, especially the elderly, children and those
suffering from allergies, to stay away from central Tehran where
pollution has gone "beyond dangerous levels."
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately even in a normal situation over 500 tonnes of
hydrocarbons, 120 tonnes of nitrogen monoxide, five to 20 tonnes
of lead from car emissions enter the air in the capital city
every day, he said.
</P>
<P>
Following the serious air pollution during recent days, Tehran
authorities shut down elementary schools in Tehran and nearby
cities of Shahr Rey and Shemiranat on Monday to protect children
from the air pollution.
</P>
<P>
The education department of Tehran province announced on Monday
to close all elementary, secondary and high schools in the three
cities upon a recommendation made by the Environment Protection
Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
