<HEADLINE> Iraq FM: Prolonging Sanctions Against U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Prolonging the economic
sanctions on Iraq is not in conformity with U.N. resolutions,
rather it is out of political motives, said Iraqi Foreign
Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf made the remark at the second conference of Non-aligned
Students and Youth Organization held here.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq's response to the international initiatives since last
February was to achieve the main goal of lifting sanctions, but
the American administration insists on prolonging it," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq has fully cooperated with the United Nations
Special Commission (UNSCOM) and the International Atomic Energy
Agency (IAEA) in arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq following its 1990 invasion
of Kuwait cannot be lifted unless U.N. arms inspectors verify that
Iraq is free of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, 880 UNSCOM teams have inspected 811 Iraqi sites and
installed 16 camera systems to monitor Iraqi industrial
establishments, he said, adding that 13,500 tonnes of chemical
materials and 400 missiles have been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Laboratory tests in Switzerland and France proved that Iraq did
not weaponize the lethal nerve gas VX, said Sahhaf.
</P>
<P>
He said that the international community needs to be informed
of the facts concerning disarmament in Iraq and must defend Iraq's
legitimate rights and confront disinformation campaigns launched
against Iraq to distort the facts.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler will submit a report Tuesday to
the U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on whether Iraq has kept
its promise of full cooperation with U.N. arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
In mid-November, Iraq announced unconditional resumption of
full cooperation with U.N. arms inspections it suspended three
months ago, narrowly escaping a U.S.-led punishing air strike.
</P>
</TEXT>
