<HEADLINE> De Beers Sales Drop by 28 Percent in 1997/98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The sales of rough gem
diamonds by De Beers in 1998 registered 3.345 billion U.S.
Dollars, 28 percent less than the previous year's 4.840 Dollars,
the diamond giant said in a statement Monday.
</P>
<P>
The sales in the second half of 1998 were 1,645 billion
Dollars, seven percent less than that during the same period in
1997, said De Beers.
</P>
<P>
It said that trading conditions were difficult throughout the
year and the expectations that sales in the second half would be
higher than the first half failed to materialize.
</P>
<P>
"Good levels of retail sales of diamond jewelry in the
United States and to a lesser extent in Europe have been
insufficient to compensate for lower sales in Japan and East
Asia," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
In the U.S., retail sales during the first half of 1998 were
some seven percent higher than the previous year. Early
indications are that sales during the important Christmas season
will also be up compared with last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the company said, retail demand in Japan, the second
largest market, is some 20 percent below the 1997 level in Dollar
terms.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's polished diamond imports have been running at
about 40 percent below 1997 levels.
</P>
<P>
Owing to poor sales figures, De Beers' headline earnings
slipped by 33 percent in the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
The low level of sales in the second half will also impact
results for the current financial year to December 1998, it
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
