<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Struggles for Attracting Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 14 (Xinhua) -- A regular session of the
Consultative Council for Foreign Investments in Russia held here
behind closed doors on Monday adopted a special communique,
according to the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov told the session that
the August 17, 1998 decisions of the government of the Russian
Federation and the Central Bank became the catalysts of the
negative processes. Russia is in crisis.
</P>
<P>
Under the current circumstances the key tasks facing the
Russian government is to "ensure the operation of life-support
systems and reduce social tension," the communique says.
</P>
<P>
The Council discussed concrete measures, which include tax
reform, bringing accounting practices in line with international
standards, developing the financial sector and the securities
market, enhancing investment insurance, perfecting customs
procedures, removing trade and non-trade barriers for Russian
exports, invigorating foreign investments in the Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government, in cooperation with the parliament,
will adopt the Civil Code and laws on foreign investments in the
Russian Federation, on the list of industries, on the introduction
of legislative acts, on concession agreements concluded with
Russian and foreign investors, and on free economic zone.
</P>
<P>
The adoption of these laws will create a national regime and
stable conditions for foreign investors, settle disputes with
neutral international arbitration, the freedom of profit
repatriation and state guarantees for the foreign investments, the
communique said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the government will continue its efforts to
attract foreign investments and to improve organizational forms of
this work.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
