<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., DPRK Agree to Continue Joint MIA search </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States and the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) have agreed to
continue their joint search next year for the remains of American
soldiers missing in action during the 1950-53 Korean War, the
Pentagon announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement for a total of six joint search operations
between April and November of next year was reached following
four days of talks that began in New York last Wednesday, the
announcement said.
</P>
<P>
"We have hammered out an agreement that take us far beyond
our three previous years' operations," said Bob Jones, deputy
assistant defense secretary for POW/Missing Personnel Affairs.
</P>
<P>
"We formalized the concept of a joint investigation team to
locate and interview witnesses to accelerate the pace of
recovery long before our excavation teams begin their work. This
concept gives us the potential to recover more remains by using
our people more efficiently," he added.
</P>
<P>
It will be the fourth consecutive year that the United States
has conducted recovery operations in the DPRK with the help of
DPRK teams. In nine joint operations over the past three years,
U.S.-DPRK teams have recovered remains believed to be those of
29 U.S. troops from the 1950-53 war.
</P>
<P>
The agreement reached in New York also included two joint
archival reviews in which U.S. officials will be granted access
to documents in the DPRK relating to U.S. personnel lost or
captured during the war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
