<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Still Confident of Lockerbie Surrender </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 14 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Monday voiced his confidence again in the Libyan
move to hand over the two suspects of the 1988 Lockerbie
airliner bombing.
</P>
<P>
Annan told a press conference that "My sense is that we are
near a decision and I think they will move in the right decision.
My sense is that they have realized they have come to the end of
the road. And I think they will move in the right direction."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief made the statement following his December 5
talks with Libyan leader Muammar Gadaffi in a bid to press Tripoli
to surrender the two suspects for the trial in the Netherlands. He
has described the talks as "fruitful and positive."
</P>
<P>
The two Libyans were accused of planting a bomb aboard Pan Am
flight 301, which exploded in mid-air over Lockerbie, Scotland,
killing a total of 270 people.
</P>
<P>
At issue is where the two suspects, if convicted, to serve
their sentences. Libya, which has accepted in August the U.S.-UK
proposal to hold the trial before a Scottish court in the
Netherlands, is against a joint proposal by Washington and London
to have the two serve their sentences in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
Libya is currently holding a session of the People's Congress,
the nation's top legislative body, which would have to endorse any
decision by Gaddafi to surrender the two men, Abdel Basset Ali
Mohammed Al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah.
</P>
<P>
But Annan, in his response to a question, said that he believed
such obstacles had been clarified and that Libya was aware of the
10th anniversary of the bombing next Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, he declined to predict when the handover would take
place, just repeating his previous statement that it would not
take "an inordinate amount of time."
</P>
<P>
U.N. sanctions, imposed in 1992 and tightened in 1993, would
be suspended automatically once the two arrived in the
Netherlands, said a Security Council resolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Camp in W. Tanzania to Be Used for DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) plans to use a new camp in west
Tanzania's Kigoma Region next month to accommodate refugees from
the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Jean Durieux, head of the UNHCR Kigoma sub-office, told
reporters over the weekend that the agency expects to open the
Lugufu camp in Kigoma district because the Nyarugusu camp in
Kasulu district will be full by the end of this month with 50 new
arrivals every day on average.
</P>
<P>
Durieux said the Nyarugusu camp has over 17,000 Congolese
refugees, while its holding capacity is 20,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The Lugufu camp in Kigoma district is presently holding about
9,000 Congolese refugees who entered the country in 1996, the
UNHCR official said, adding that with the on-going wars in the
DRC, the process of repatriating these refugees to their country
is halted.
</P>
<P>
"If the influx rate of DRC refugees continues to rise, by mid
next year we will need a new camp because even the Lugufu camp
whose capacity is 20,000 will be filled," he said.
</P>
<P>
Durieux said his office has requested the government to
allocate a contingency site in case the influx rate kept on
rising, but has yet to receive any responses.
</P>
<P>
He explained the DRC refugees cannot be taken to Nduta camp in
Kibondo district because they cannot be mixed with those from
Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The Congolese refugees at Nyarugusu camp, some 160 kilometers
northwest of the Kigoma town on Lake Tanganyika, have formed
their own internal governing structure to maintain security and
order, Durieux said.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Ministry of Home Affairs working at the
camp, Charles Nswila, said that the camp has been divided into 12
villages in which a man and a woman are elected as the head.
Seven zones which has two presidents each are formed on the basis
of these 12 villages.
</P>
<P>
He said the system has been very helpful in resolving their
problems and only few cases were delivered to police at the camp
for handling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
