<HEADLINE> EU Clears Aid for Kosovo, Bosnia-Herzegovina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Brussels, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) said
here Monday that it had cleared humanitarian aid worth a total of
11.597 million ECUs for projects to assist victims of conflict in
Kosovo and Bosnia Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
The aid, managed by a EU aid agency, the European Community
Humanitarian Office (ECHO), will enable international and
non-governmental organizations to carry out the certain projects
over the Winter, the European Commission said.
</P>
<P>
According to the commission, the EU's executive body, the
latest grant of 10 million ECUs (11.8 million U.S.dollars) brings
the total provided for the crisis in Kosovo this year to 19
million ECUs (22.4 million U.S. dollars). This aid will help all
those displaced with food, health care and shelter.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that conflict in Kosovo led to about 300,000
people being displaced. Many left Kosovo for Montenegro, Albania,
the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia, Bosnia and Herzegovina,
Turkey and other parts of Serbia. But many still stayed in Kosovo
itself and face hardship this Winter.
</P>
<P>
In Bosnia and Herzegovina, Winter temperatures can plunge to
-20 degrees, with snow until the end of April, the commission
said. There are still more than 800,000 internally displaced
people, and some groups are particularly vulnerable. The EU grant
of 1.579 million ECUs (1.86 million U.S.dollars) will provide
fuel, Winter clothes as well as enabling repairs to electricity
and water supply systems.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
