<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-14 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Welcomes PNC Decision on Revoking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu welcomed Monday the reaffirmation by the
Palestine National Council (PNC) of the annulment of anti-Israel
clauses in the Palestinian charter but demanded more Palestinian
steps.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said at a news conference here that the PNC decision
to reaffirm the revocation of the anti-Israel provisions is "a very
important and positive step" which will help move forward the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
He noted that this was the first time that the Palestinian
leadership have declared publicly to their people that all the
provisions in the charter calling for the destruction of Israel
have been null and void.
</P>
<P>
"It's an important day for the state of Israel," he said.
</P>
<P>
But the prime minister also described this move only as the
first step and insisted that the Palestinians take more measures
to fulfill their obligations.
</P>
<P>
He made a list of measures the Palestinians need to take
before Israel agrees to hand over more land in the West Bank to
them, including stopping anti-Israel incitements, collecting
illegal weapons and arresting terrorists.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Israel would not release those Palestinian
prisoners "with bloods on their hands."
</P>
<P>
His acceptance of the PNC decision has cleared a final
obstacle to a three-way summit with Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat and visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that the summit will take place Tuesday
morning at the Erez border crossing between Israel and the
Palestinian-rule Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting at the Shawa Center in the afternoon, almost all
PNC members stood up and raised their hands to show their support
when asked by Arafat to reaffirm the nullification of anti-Israel
clauses in the charter.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that by rejecting the offensive clauses "fully,
finally and forever," the PNC, the Palestinian parliament in
exile, has sent "a powerful message (of peace), not to the
government, but to the people of Israel."
</P>
<P>
"You've touched the people of Israel, you've reached out to
their heart there," he said, with his remarks greeted by a long
applause by the members.
</P>
<P>
The PNC meeting is the centerpiece of Clinton's three-day
visit to Israel and the Palestinian areas, which started Sunday,
and a key element of the recent land-for-peace deal signed by
Arafat and Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The reaffirmation put an end to the prolonged dispute over the
Palestinian charter between Israel and the palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The PNC voted in April 1996 to revoke the anti-Israel clauses
in the Palestinian charter and the former Israeli Labor
government has accepted the vote.
</P>
<P>
But when Netanyahu came to power one month later, he said the
PNC vote was not complete and demanded the PNC convene again.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli prime minister put the recent peace deal on hold
last week amid violent clashes in the West Bank which were
sparked by Israel's refusal to release so-called security
prisoners and what he said was Arafat's unilateral declaration of
a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with local TV after the PNC meeting, senior
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat urged Netanyahu not to look
for excuse to avoid the implementation of the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Israel has carried out the first of three withdrawals in line
with the agreement last month. The second stage of Israeli troop
redeployment is due to start this weekend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
