<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Financial Turmoil Blamed for Turkey's Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Finance Minister
Zekeriya Temizel said here Monday that Turkey is being influenced
by an external financial crisis and should focus on getting rid of
this panic-driven crisis mood.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Temizel said that "the Turkish
economy is not in a crisis now, but it was significantly affected
by an external crisis."
</P>
<P>
Temizel and State Minister Isin Celebi explained detailed
economic measures that were decided in the cabinet and were
announced by caretaker Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz.
</P>
<P>
Temizel said the crises that erupted in East Asia and Russia
scared international investors and that as as a result, capital
started flowing to secure countries from risky markets.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey was affected by this crisis because it was put in the
same category with other risky emerging market economies," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that "what is important is voicing and
discussing problems and looking for a solution within the
framework of social consensus. And this is what we are trying to
do."
</P>
<P>
"The Turkish economy is not a mandated one. The idea that all
intervention power belongs to the state and that the state can
convert all the negative things into positive things is wrong,"
added the minister.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Celebi said that the reason for the current
difficult situation is both the global crisis and structural
problems in the economy which started in 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
He said that the problem should not be an issue of political
conflict, adding that although companies demand solutions to their
specific short-term problems, the government has to consider the
interests of the whole country and future generations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
