<HEADLINE> ECB Says Euroland Money Growth at 4.8 per cent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Central Bank (ECB)
Monday said that money growth expansion currently poses no
inflationary dangers.
</P>
<P>
Less than three weeks before the launch of the single currency
euro in 11 European countries, the Frankfurt-based ECB said in its
first comprehensive statistical report about the money supply
situation in "Euroland", that in October the annual growth rate
was 4.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The average for the months of August, September and October was
just 4.5 percent, the ECB noted.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two years, the annual growth in money supply in
the 11 countries ranged between 3.5 and 5.5 percent. This trend is
"largely compatible with the ongoing price stability in the euro
region", the ECB said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said that in October the money supply stood at
over 4.25 trillion European Currency Units (2.65 trillion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The 11 euro-states are all but four - Britain, Greece, Denmark,
and Sweden - of the 15 European Union members.  
</P>
</TEXT>
