<HEADLINE>   Australian Team Scales Mount Amadablam in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Four members of an
Australian team scaled the 6,812-meter Mount Amadablam in Nepal
on December 5 from the southwest ridge, the Nepali Ministry of
Tourism and Civil Aviation announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ducan Charles Chessell, David John Wiltshire and Mark Auricht
from Australia and Adele M. Pennington, a female teacher from
Britain, started at Camp III (6,350 meters) at 9:30 in the
morning and reached the summit at two in the afternoon, the
ministry said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Climbers spent 30 minutes on the summit and returned to Camp
II at six in the afternoon, the ministry noted.
</P>
<P>
The five-strong Australian Amadablam Exp.1998 was led by Ducan
Charles Chessell, a 28-year-old geologist, it added.
</P>
<P>
Three teams got permission from the Nepali government to climb
two different mountains in Nepal during the winter mountaineering
season running from December 1, 1998 to February 15, 1999.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. team and a South Korean team are making attempts
respectively on Mount Amadablam and the 8,163-meter Mount
Manaslu, the world's eighth highest mountain. 
