<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN to Speed Up Economic Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The member countries of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) plan to speed up
their economic integration by advancing the timetable for
implementing the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA).
</P>
<P>
Briefing reporters on the first day of a two-day ASEAN summit
here Tuesday afternoon, Foreign Minister Nguyen Manh Cam of
Vietnam, which is chairman of the summit, said the "developed
members" of the regional grouping will fully implement AFTA by the
year 2002, instead of the original 2003, when member countries
would cut their tariffs to 0-5 percent. However, new members would
be granted "an extremely flexible" schedule and timetable.
</P>
<P>
The leaders also discussed measures to promote intra-ASEAN
investment by giving investors from other member countries
national treatment while efforts would be made to obtain
investment from outside the region.
</P>
<P>
In regard to the financial and monetary sectors, the leaders
considered measures to increase short-term capital movements, Cam
said.
</P>
<P>
The leaders also raised the idea of a common ASEAN currency,
but as it will take some time for the ASEAN to get such a
currency, the leaders have instructed officials and experts "to
study very carefully the issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese foreign minister said the leaders also stressed
the need for intensified cooperation between the ASEAN countries
and international and regional organizations in areas such as
infrastructure including the building of a trans-ASEAN railway
from Singapore through Malaysia, Cambodia, Laos, and Vietnam to
South China.
</P>
<P>
The leaders also discussed the development of sub-regions such
as the Mekong Basin, noting that sub-regional cooperation will be
a "very substantial contribution" to poverty eradication.
</P>
<P>
In order to carry out these projects, the leaders stressed the
need of coordinating policies at both macro and micro levels,
according to Cam.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state and government will continue their meeting
Wednesday morning and are expected to adopt the Hanoi Declaration,
the Hanoi Plan of Action and other documents submitted by their
foreign and economic ministers before the conclusion of the summit
at noon.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar,
the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Vietnamese foreign minister said that Cambodia
is already a member of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) although an admission ceremony is yet to be held.
</P>
<P>
"The ASEAN leaders have decided to admit Cambodia as the 10th
member of ASEAN. This is a very clear and definite decision by the
ASEAN leaders, meaning Cambodia is the 10th member of ASEAN," Cam
said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, there is a procedural question to be solved
and the ASEAN leaders have instructed their foreign ministers to
arrange an admission ceremony in Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
"So my understanding is that although the admission ceremony
has not yet occurred, Cambodia can be considered the 10th member
of ASEAN," he added. "I understand the admission ceremony will be
organized at the earliest possible time."
</P>
<P>
However, at the open session of the Sixth ASEAN Summit Tuesday
morning, Cambodian Prime Minister Hun Sen did not sit together
with leaders from the other members as his country enjoys only
observer status.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese foreign minister said the ceremony may take
place in one or two weeks or in one month, but Cambodia is now an
ASEAN member. 
</P>
</TEXT>
