<HEADLINE> ADB Supports Civil Service Reform in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) approved on Monday a technical assistance grant of 630,000
U.S. dollars to the Nepalese government to help it reform the
civil service, the bank said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The principal focus of the technical assistance project will
be to lay the groundwork for a broad reform of the civil service.
The project will be based on previous studies of the government
and other donors, especially the 1992 report of the Government
Administrative Reform Commission," the bank said in press release.
</P>
<P>
It said that the technical assistance will support preparatory
activities leading to specific reforms in the civil service.
</P>
<P>
"Upon completion of these activities, a time-bound Action Plan
for civil service reform will be prepared," the bank said. "It is
keeping with the bank's anti-corruption strategy, an action plan
for strengthening the capacity of constitutional bodies will also
be developed."
</P>
<P>
The bank said that if the Nepalese government is committed to
implementing the time-bound action plan, it would consider
providing a civil service reform policy-based assistance.
</P>
<P>
The technical assistance project is expected to start in
January 1999 and finish at the end of that year, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the total size of Nepal's civil service is
estimated at 100,000 to 140,000 people, or approximately 0.57
civil servants per hundred population, which is relatively small
by developing country standards.
</P>
<P>
It noted that a number of studies described the civil service
as being politicized, inefficient and ineffective.
</P>
<P>
The Government Administrative Reform Commission had concluded
that the civil service was seriously overextended and its sphere
of operations needed significant reduction, the bank added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
