<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Prices Rise 0.2 Pct in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. consumer prices edged
up moderately in November as inflation remained temperate in the
economy, the Labor Department said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Consumer Price Index, the so-called core inflation rate,
rose just 0.2 percent last month after an identical increase in
October. This is the fifth consecutive month of this modest
reading. So far this year, the inflation rate is rising at an
annual rate of 2.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. consumers have got benefits from the world economic
chaos, which has sent the prices of a number of goods, including
oil, down to their lowest levels in a decade. Although food prices
rose slightly by 0.1 percent in November, the prices of
vegetables, oranges, pork and poultry all showed declines.
</P>
