<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Secondary HIV Victims Get Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Canadians infected with the HIV
from tainted blood will each receive 240,000 Canadian dollars
(156,000 U.S.dollars) in compensation, the Ottawa Citizen
newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The federal-provincial government compensation scheme could
cost 48 million Canadian dollars (31 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The lump-sum payments will go to a group of people, the
"secondarily infected," who have often been overlooked in the
tainted-blood tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this decade, federal and provincial governments
provided compensation packages for AIDS victims who got the
disease directly from blood supplies.
</P>
<P>
The federal package gave 120,000 Canadian dollars (78,000
U.S. dollars) over four years, while a provincial scheme
guaranteed 30,000 Canadian dollars (21,000 U.S. dollars) a year
for life.
</P>
<P>
But those who were secondarily infected did not qualify for
either program and have waged a persistent campaign ever since for
similar treatment.
</P>
<P>
Johanne Decarie, who lives in Hawkeshury, east of Ottawa, has
been at the forefront in pushing for extended compensation.
</P>
<P>
Decarie was infected with tainted blood in 1985. Later, she
unknowingly infected her husband, Bill, and gave birth to an
HIV-positive girl, Billie Jo, now nine years old.
</P>
<P>
"I'm relieved they will finally be recognized as victims of a
system that failed them," she said, "It's been a long wait, a long
battle." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
