<HEADLINE> Reform Pioneer Announces Plan for Next Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Andrew Browne, China bureau
chief for Reuters, today interviewed Zhang Gaoli, a leading
official in the city of Shenzhen which pioneered China's reform
and opening effort.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, secretary of the Shenzhen City Communist Party of China
Committee, outlined the city's blueprint for developing a modern
international metropolis over the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
For the past 20 years, Shenzhen has grown from a small town to
a rapidly developing hub with annual GDP growth rate of 33
percent, said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The city, which has established the framework for an
export-oriented economy, with 38 percent of its industrial output
value produced by high and new technological industries.
</P>
<P>
Zhang noted the 1979 comments late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping
made concerning what the special economic zone would be able to
achieve in 20 years. He said the deeping of reform has allowed
other Chinese cities to the narrow gaps and virtually reduce for
economic zones.
</P>
<P>
The city urgently needs to upgrade its industries and
accelerate urban construction, according to Zhang.
</P>
<P>
"Shenzhen is currently drafting plans for the construction of
the Futian downtown area. The new area will include a 320,000
sq.m. square and will rank second only to Tian'anmen Square in
terms of size." said Zhang, "The city is expected to allocate
several hundred million yuan for the project."
</P>
<P>
The interview provided valuable material for a Reuters series
covering changes during China's 20 years of reform and opening.
</P>
