<HEADLINE> China's Economy on Faster Track in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- China's economy picked up in
November according to the country's National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
In figures released today the added value of china's industrial
sector last month registered an 11 percent growth rate on a
year-on-year basis, 0.4 percent higher than in October.
</P>
<P>
In the January-November period, the sector's added value rose
to 1802.7 billion yuan, an increase of 8.5 percent over the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
In November, the fixed assets investment of State-owned
companies increased by 28.9 percent over the same period last
year. In the first 11 months of the year, the fixed assets
investment increased by 22.3 percent on a year-on-year basis.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales in the period was 7.4 percent up from the same
period last year, the Bureau reported. In urban areas the growth
rate reached 8.1 percent, while standing at 6.4 percent in rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
However, the statistics show that exports in November were
worth 15.1 billion U.S. dollars, a year-on-year decrease of 9.7
percent; 7.5 percent lower than in October. The month's imports
amounted to 12.3 billion U.S. dollars, up 2.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Prices continued to fall during the period, and the retail
price index fell 2.8 percent with the consumer price index down
1.2 percent compared to the same period last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
