<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Li Lanqing Calls for Financial Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Li Lanqing
attended today's national conference on finance and noted that
China's economic development during 1999 will depend on public
finance.
</P>
<P>
The fulfillment of budgeted revenues and expenditures for 1999
will be vitally important for strengthening the relationship
between reform, development and stability, said Li.
</P>
<P>
China must carry out an active fiscal policy in order to
increase domestic demand and ensure moderate economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Top priority should be placed on ensuring adequate funding for
infrastructure projects and fulfilling budgeted targets for
expenditures. General purpose funding should be reduced by a wide
margin, according to Zhang.
</P>
<P>
He called on financial departments at all levels to alter
operating concepts, find new sources of revenue and reduce
expenditures in order to fulfill financial tasks set for 1999.
</P>
<P>
Reform of tax collection management will be proceed in a
rational manner, and the government faces a significant risk
related to the practice of redefining fees as taxes.
</P>
<P>
The leader said effective measures must be adopted to introduce
a tax system suited to the development of a socialist market
economy.
</P>
<P>
Departments of finance, taxation and planning should join in a
three-year campaign to devise a system which will halt
collection of illicit fees, according to Li. 
</P>
</TEXT>
