<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Following are major economic
briefs from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- The European Union has announced that it will finance
three projects in Morocco to the tune of 69 million ECUs (nearly
80 million U.S. dollars) of which 28 million will be earmarked for
the development of forest sector, 6 million for the communications
sector, and 35 million for small projects.
</P>
<P>
The European financing is part of an EU plan to invigorate the
economy of the region, and an overall assistance program of 411
million dollars for about 12 difference projects in the region.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Arab monetary fund has extended a loan as well
as technical assistance to Jordan, which amount to 16.8 million
dollars, to support the economic reforms which Jordan will embark
on next year.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- An international defense exhibition and convention
"EDEX 99" will open here next March.
</P>
<P>
The chairman of the military committee in charge of the
organization of the exhibition Brigadier-General Sultan Obeid Al
Sweidi estimated the needs of the Gulf region for modern weapons
and defense equipment at approximately 80 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Reports recently received by the Egyptian National
Assembly on economic and trade cooperation between Egypt and Libya
said that Libya is seeking to increase its investments in Egypt to
3 billion dollars by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The reports added that Libyan investments in Egypt have
exceeded 1 billion Egyptian pounds (294 million dollars), covering
100 projects in industry, agriculture, tourism and other financial
and services projects.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- An American delegation representing 30 companies is
due to come to Cairo next January to examine investment
opportunities in the field of ecological technology, Tuesday's
Egyptian daily "Alam Al Yom" said.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will hold a series of meetings with Egyptian
businessmen on environment protection projects.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Public Business Sector Atef
Ebeid said Egypt's external debts have declined from 46 billion
dollars to 26 billion dollars partly because the United States and
the Arab states decided to exempt Egypt from part of its debts.
</P>
<P>
He added that the remaining debts would be settled by the year
2026. 
</P>
