<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Expected to Promote Sino-European Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The euro, which will be
launched on New Year's Day 1999, is expected to greatly promote
trade between China and all European nations, including members of
the Europan Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Experts attending today's opening session of an international
seminar on the possible impact the euro will have on the Chinese
economy and financial sector.
</P>
<P>
Yang Zilin, vice president of the China Industrial and
Commercial Bank (CICB), addressed the long-term point of view and
noted that the euro will have a positive impact on Sino-European
trade relations. He also noted that a stable and reliable euro
will provide a good vehicle for the further development of
Sino-European trade.
</P>
<P>
He added that the emerging euro will provide greater
convenience for Sino-European trade settlements, reduce risks
related to exchange rate risks and lower risk management costs.
</P>
<P>
"The euro will also help alleviate China's overdependence on
Sino-U.S. trade, and help to develop a more diversified foreign
trade structure needed to increase exports," according to Yang.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Wenming, director of the European Division under the
International Trade Institute in Beijing, said the euro will
simplify trade settlements between China and the EU and in turn
reduce costs and risks related to exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
"It will be no longer necessary for Chinese enterprises to
open offices in all EU countries, with a single office serving the
needs of all EU members," said Zhou, adding that expanding role of
the euro in trade settlements will reduce China's dependence on
the US dollar.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for the first nine months of this year show that the
total trade volume between China and EU countries hit 33.89
billion US dollars, up 16.6 percent on the 1997 period. The export
volume grew 21.7 percent to end the period at 20.27 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The EU ranks as China's fourth largest export market and second
largest supplier for imported goods.
</P>
<P>
Yang said the euro will also help EU members increase
investments in China and allow the latter to expand its
participation in the European capital market.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese enterprises will be able to make better use of the
unified European capital market by issuing bonds in euro to raise
funds at a comparatively low cost. Qualified listed enterprises
can also issue shares to raise funds on the European capital
market," according to Yang.
</P>
<P>
The experts also pointed possible unfavorable influences the
euro will have on Sino-European trade, including intensified
regional protectionism, increased costs for enterprise upgrades
and risks involving exchange rates.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
