<HEADLINE> China Wins Two Volleyball Golds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 15 (Xinhua) -- China became the biggest
winner in Asiad volleyball matches as its men's and women's teams
defeated their archrivals South Korea in both finals on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In the women's final, the Chinese spikers took revenge of the
South Korean team, who beat China in the 1994 Hiroshima Asian
Games and last month's world championship in Japan.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese overpowered the South Korean team 3-1 in last
Friday's preliminary round match. But despite the victory, Lang
Ping, the Chinese head coach, said that neither of the two teams
has the absolute power to win the gold.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's match proved what she said, as the two fought a hard
battle before the Chinese won 15-6, 13-15, 15-8 and 15-13.
</P>
<P>
"The South Korean team is great in controlling the rhythm,"
Lang said after the match, "but our players also made the best
performance."
</P>
<P>
"We met our expectation," said Lang, who was famous as the
spiker of Chinese team when it took five successive titles in
World Championship, World Cup and Olympic Games in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
In the third place playoff, Japan beat host Thailand for the
bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese men's team, as the newly-crowned Asian champions,
won a much easier match against South Korea 15-7, 15-11, 10-15 and
15-9.
</P>
<P>
The head coach, Wang Jiawei, who was also a spiker, said though
as the champion of Asia, China will not remain what they are.
</P>
<P>
"Instead, we will march on, march on to the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, according to Yuan Weimin, President of the Asian
Volleyball Federation, volleyball in Asia is becoming weaker, as
"the best men's team in Asia only holds the 13th place in the
world."
</P>
<P>
In the bronze medal match earlier on Tuesday, Chinese Taipei
defeated defending champion Japan 3-2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
