<HEADLINE> China Reaches Target of Winning Four Cycling Golds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 15 (Xinhua) -- China's cyclists have reached
the target of obtaining four golds when they finished one-two in
women's 3-km individual pursuit while securing another gold in
women's sprint here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Wang Qingzhi, 30, successful defended her Asian Games pursuit
title by beating compatriot Zhao Haijuan to second. Zhao won the
silver while South Korea's Kim Yong Mi the bronze.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who set the Games record at Hiroshima four years ago,
said she now wanted to concentrate more on her provincial coaching
job and phased out from competition.
</P>
<P>
"I could also make room for the newcomers like Zhao," added the
national champion.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 4-km pursuit it was also the title defender that
excelled.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan's Vadim Kravchenko, who set Games record four years
ago, retained his title by beating Japan's Noriyuki Iijima.
</P>
<P>
"I want to dedicate this medal to my wife and 5-year-old son,"
said Kravchenko, a 30-year-old Army lietnant.
</P>
<P>
In the race for the third place, Kyrgyzstan's Evgeniy Vakker
beat China's Shi Guijun to win the bronze.
</P>
<P>
In the women's semifinals, which were both held between Chinese
and Chinese Taipei riders, China triumphed as Wang Yan beat Lu Yi
Wen while Jiang Cuihua defeated Fang Fen Fang.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Wang and Jiang, 25, will meet each other on
Thursday's final while the two Chinese Taipei cyclists vie for the
bronze.
</P>
<P>
China's team leader Li Xin said now with four golds in hand,
the team hopes to strike gold in the women's road race. Earlier
China had won women's road time trial and women's mountain bike
cross country golds.
</P>
<P>
In the men's sprints, Yuichiro Kamiyama and Noriaki Mabuchi,
professional cyclists in Japan's popular Keirin races, won over
their respective rivals.
</P>
<P>
Mabuchi, who will clash against Keirin champion Kamiyama for
the gold on Wednesday, said Kamiyama is strong but not unbeatable.
</P>
<P>
"I would challenge him tommorrow. I have a good tactics in my
mind now but I would not tell you. It is a secret," said
27-year-old Mabuchi after beating China's Liu Yadong 2-0. 
</P>
