<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Claims Team Titles in Bangkok Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 15 (Xinhua) -- China took three team titles
on Tuesday to increase its gold tally to 92, manifesting clearly
its statue of sports giant in the 47-year history of Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
In both the men's and women's volleyball tournaments, China
regained its Asian titles by beating archrival South Korea in both
finals.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese women spikers, once dominated the world by claiming
five straight titles from the World Cup, the World Championships
and the Olympics in the 1980's, regained their Asian crown by
dethroning South Korea 15-6, 13-15, 15-8 and 15-13 for a
morale-boosting revenge against the defeats in the Hiroshima Asiad
and in the World Championship last month.
</P>
<P>
Their men compatriots, winners in the Asian Championships and
the best Asian squad ranked 13th in the World Championship, also
swept aside South Korea 15-7, 15-11, 10-15 and 15-9 to regain the
title lost to Japan four years ago in Hiroshima.
</P>
<P>
"We're gald that our volleyball players have regained their
Asian titles, but we cannot indulge ourselves in the victories as
we still do not have the clear dominance in Asia," said Yuan
Weimin, former head coach for the Chinese women team who currently
serves as the president of the Asian Volleyball Federation.
</P>
<P>
"Winning the Asian Games is not the end but the beginning for
our men volleyball players," said head coach Wang Jiawei, a former
ace spiker who took the helm of the national team after the
Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
In another team event of the day, the Chinese quartet of Wang
Haibin, Dong Zhaozhi, Lin Liang and Liu Yuntao outbeat their
Japanese peers 45-35 to take the men's team foil fencing title.
</P>
<P>
However, from the track and field which produced the most of
six golds of the day, China bagged home two through its women
athletes while Japan got three, all through its men competitors.
</P>
<P>
After three-day competitions, China still lags behind 8-9 in
the gold tally against Japan in the athletics where 23 out of 43
gold medals have been grabbed away.
</P>
<P>
Li Xuemei and Koji Ito, winners in the women's and men's 100
meters respectively, anchored vicotries for their countries in the
4x100m relays on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Li led the Chinese women's quartet to the win in 43.36 seconds
because "we are much stronger than the others and I am very
confident despite a weak health after being hospitalized for the
whole last night due to a fever."
</P>
<P>
Koji, who set an Asian record of 10.00 seconds in the men's
100m semifinals, sealed the win for the Japanese foursome in 38.91
while the Chinese was out of rhythm in the third batch.
</P>
<P>
China had its other athletics gold through 39-year-old Li Meisu
in the women's shot put who once retired in 1988 and backed to the
field last year, while Japan won two more through Yasunori
Uchitomi in the 3,000m steeplechase and Masaki Morinaga in the
long jump.
</P>
<P>
However the most golds for Japan were from the women's karatedo
where they swept all four but one as Atsuko Wakai got the kata
title, Eri Fugioka triumphed in the 53-kg kumite and Izumi Nabeki
won the over 60-kg kumite, with Li Wan-Yu of Chinese Taipei
crowned in the 60-kg kumite.
</P>
<P>
The table tennis remains to be a Chinese castle as Wan Nan won
the women's singles in an all-Chinese final against Li Ju and Liu
Guoliang and Kong Linghui outwitted their South Korean rivals in
straight sets in the men's doubles.
</P>
<P>
In the cycling sprint semifinals of the day, China has ensured
a gold and a silver in the women's event while Japan was also
guaranteed a one-two finish in the men's final.
</P>
<P>
The women's semifinals witnessed two contests between China and
Chinese Taipei, and China triumphed as Wang Yan beat Lu Yi-Wen
while Jiang Cuihua defeated Fang Fen-Fang.
</P>
<P>
The men's sprints featured two professionals of Yuichiro
Kamiyama and Noriaki Mabuchi who triumphed for an inner bickerning
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
With all the competitions concluded on Tuesday, China stands
lonely in the gold tally with 92, while South Korea who reapt only
three, ranked in a distant second with 45, closely chased by Japan
with 42. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
