<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Australian Economy Grows Strongly in Face of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Australia, the 14th largest
economy in the world which has close economic and trade links with
Asia, has in the past 18 months weathered the Asian economic
crisis far better than most people had predicted.
</P>
<P>
Ian Macfarlane, governor of the Reserve Bank of Australia, the
country's central bank, predicted Tuesday the Australian economy
would grow by 4 percent in 1998 over the previous year, compared
with 3 percent he forecast earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics released earlier this month by the
Australian Bureau of Statistics, the Australian economy grew by 5
percent in the year to September with inflation around 1.8 percent
and the jobless rate at an eight-year low of 7.7 percent in
October, and 8 percent in November.
</P>
<P>
The Australian economy was up by 3.9 percent in the past
financial year ending on June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The central bank governor admitted Tuesday that "Australia's
economic performance has exceeded our expectations, and, to the
best of my knowledge, the expectations of virtually all
forecasters."
</P>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard recently also expressed
his surprise at the strength of the economy.
</P>
<P>
"We are enjoying economic growth which is even stronger than
the more optimistic of us thought possible six or nine months
ago," he said.
</P>
<P>
Three months ago, however, the Australian federal government
and leading economic forecasters painted a gloomy picture when
Asia, Russia and Latin America were in economic turmoil and the
United States' economy seemed to slow down.
</P>
<P>
They warned of slower growth in the Australian economy, rising
inflation and unemployment, arguing that the crisis would lead to
weak demand for Australian products from Asia, which buys about 60
percent of the goods and services Australia exports annually.
</P>
<P>
In addition, they said the weak Australian currency, which has
fallen by about 20 percent against the U.S. dollar since the
crisis, would push up inflation as the prices of many imported
consumer goods would go up.
</P>
<P>
Against such a background, the government in September revised
down its forecast of the growth rate for the current financial
year ending on June 60, 1999, cutting the forecast to 2.75 percent
from its budget target of 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The original forecast, which was made two months before the
eruption of the Asian crisis, was 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Even the 2.75 percent forecast was once considered too
optimistic by some economists.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank, the country's biggest bank, was then
among the most pessimistic about the economy, predicting an
economic growth of just 1.75 percent for this financial year.
</P>
<P>
The latest official economic figures, however, portrayed a
totally different picture.
</P>
<P>
Government officials and the central bank attributed the strong
economic performance to the sound economic management of the
Howard government, strong domestic demand, diversified export
strategy and the country's floating foreign exchange system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Cautious on Report of Lockerbie Trial in Neutral Country </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The United Kingdom on Tuesday
cautiously welcomed reports that the Libyan People's Congress had
agreed to try the two Libyan suspects of the Lockerbie bombing in
a neutral country.
</P>
<P>
"If it is true, it is good news. But at the moment it is only
a Libyan media report. We have to be circumspect unless and until
we have a formal response," said a Foreign Office spokesman,
adding that Libya must make a formal response through the office
of the U.N. Secretary-General.
</P>
<P>
Reuters reported earlier that the Libyan People's Congress, the
country's top legislative body, had expressed its agreement with a
plan for trying the two Libyan men in a neutral country.
</P>
<P>
The congress also called on the three parties involved in the
case -- Libya, Britain and the United States, to "remove any
obstacle" preventing the trial from going ahead as soon as
possible, the Reuters report quoted the Libyan television as
saying.
</P>
<P>
On December 21, 1988, a Pan Am airplane was bombed over the
Scottish town of Lockerbie, killing 270 people. The United States
and Britain accused two Libyan agents of planning and blowing up
the airliner.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the three relevant countries agreed to let
Scottish judges try the two suspects at a special court in the
Hague, Netherlands. But Libya latter refused to hand over the two
for alleged safety reasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
