<HEADLINE> China to Play Tough Semifinal Match Against Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Red cards will probably take
the Chinese toll in the Asian Games soccer semifinals Wednesday
when China faces Iran in their second encounter in five days at
the Asian Games soccer competition.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese team, which brought a largely young squad to the
games, is still looking to avenge a pair of defeats against Iran
that kept the Chinese out of the World Cup in France this year.
</P>
<P>
However, in last week's preliminary round match, Iran defeated
China 2-1. The Englishman coaching China, Bobby Houghton, said
that most of his players hadn't been called to the national side
until recently and have no inherent defeatist complex against
Iran.
</P>
<P>
But the absence of ace Chinese striker Hao Haidong, who scored
a goal Monday against Turkmenistan but was sent off after
disputing a yellow card, could fatally weaken China in what would
always have been a tough game.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese will rely on the scoring talents of Li Jinyu, who
put in the other two goals in the 3-0 shutout of Turkmenistan for
a games total of six, but are again likely to suffer against the
bigger, bruising Iranians in mid-field.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian side, packed with World Cup veterans, has clearly
emerged as the favorite for gold.
</P>
<P>
In the other semifinals, host Thailand will take on Kuwait.
Thai Manager Thawatchai Sajakul told a news conference Tuesday
that Thailand's stunning quarterfinal triumph over South Korea was
a "miracle" that could be repeated and take Thailand to the
finals. 
</P>
