<HEADLINE> China Closer to Title Sweep in Table Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The all-mighty Chinese table
tennis team proved too strong for the rest of Asia as they
boosted their title collection to five in the Asian Games here
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
World and Olympic champions Kong Linghui and Liu Guoliang
easily won the men's doubles following the 1-2 finish by Chinese
at the women's singles.
</P>
<P>
Kong and Liu, who have been nearly invincible since pairing
up in 1995, handed a 21-17, 21-13 defeat to the South Korean duo
of Lee Chul-Seung and Oh Sang-Eun.
</P>
<P>
Liu's wickedly deceptive serves and Kong's follow-up attacks
were just too much for the South Koreans, who made the final by
nipping Chiang Peng-Lung and Chang Yen-Shu from Chinese Taipei.
</P>
<P>
Chiang and Chang finished joint third with their teammates Wu
Wen-Chia and Kuo Chih-Hsiang.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, world No. 3 Wang Nan downed No. 2 Li Ju in the
all-Chinese women's singles final.
</P>
<P>
The 18-year-old Wang, who has won the World Cup twice, both at
the expense of Li, triumphed 21-14, 21-10, 21-10.
</P>
<P>
In the semifinals, Wang downed South Korean Ryu Ji-Hae and Li
beat 1996 Olympic silver medalist Chen Jing of Chinese Taipei,
both in four sets.
</P>
<P>
Ryu and Chen shared the third place.
</P>
<P>
Li and Wang reached the women's doubles semifinals on Tuesday,
beating the DPR Korean pair of Tu Jung-Sil and Wi Pok-Sun in three
sets.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's top duo of Park Hae-Jung and Kim Moo-Kyo
suffered an upset by Xu Jing and Chen Chiu-Tan of Chinese
Taipei, while the Chinese combination of Yang Ying and Wu Na
also crashed out, losing to South Korea's Ryue Ji-Hae and Lee
Eun-Sil in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
The other semifinal berth went to Chan Tan-Lui and Song
Ah-Sim from Hong Kong, China, who beat Japanese An Konishi and
Keiko Okazaki.
</P>
<P>
World No. 2 Liu Guoliang and No. 3 Kong Linghui both made the
men's singles semifinals. They will take on South Koreans Oh
Sang-Eun and Kim Taek Soo on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
China has also won the men's and women's team titles and the
mixed doubles top honor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
