<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright promised Tuesday to provide Jordan with 200
million U.S. dollars in security assistance in addition to some
250 million dollars of annual economic aid.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who is in Amman to brief Jordanian leaders on U.S
President Bill Clinton's Middle East trip, reiterated
U.S. commitments to creating more economic opportunities for the
Jordanian people, adding that her country would also strive to
meet Jordan's security needs.
</P>
<P>
She said at a press conference that she had briefed Jordanian
Crown Prince Hassan, the Regent, on the latest developments in the
Mideast peace process, the just-concluded summit meetings between
President Clinton, Israeli and Palestinian leaders and Clinton's
visit to Gaza, the first-ever visit to Palestinian self-rule areas
by a U. S. president.
</P>
<P>
Hassan thanked the U.S government for its efforts to revive the
peace process between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Albright also paid tribute to what she called "courageous
roles" played by Jordanian King Hussein and the Jordanian
government in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Albright was scheduled to return to Israel later in the day to
join Clinton's entourage on a flight back home.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, which signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994, is a
supporter of U.S. peace efforts in the Middle East. 
</P>
