<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore to Further Promote Financial Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Monetary Authority of
Singapore (MAS) said Tuesday that its efforts to promote
Singapore's financial sector were reaping results and it will step
up its drive to boost Singapore's standing as a premier financial
center.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Tan Chek Ming, executive
director of the Financial Sector Promotion Department (FPD) under
the MAS said despite the regional crisis and the slower economic
growth in the past year, there has been positive development in
the Singapore financial sector.
</P>
<P>
More key financial players were expanding their activities in
Singapore and more than a dozen financial institutions and
multinationals have obtained approval from MAS in the past year to
base their operational headquarters and finance and treasury
centers in the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tan said that total treasury revenue for the first half of this
year hit 2.8 billion Singapore dollars (about 1.7 billion U.S.
dollars), already more than half of last year's figure of 4.6
billion Singapore dollars (about 2.8 billion U.S. dollars.)
</P>
<P>
Tan also mentioned that the Singapore International Money
Exchange attracted an average daily trading volume of around
99,200 contracts in the first three quarters of this year,
compared with 94,000 contracts in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The FPD led by Tan was set up in April 1998 and has been
assigned to foster a progressive financial sector, to enhance the
IT infrastructure and develop manpower capability for the
industry.
</P>
<P>
According to Tan, FPD's efforts covered asset management, debt
market, bond, equity, and insurance and they were focused on
external communications, monitoring systems, employment monitoring
and clearing and settlement systems.
</P>
<P>
Tan said his country will press ahead with financial reforms to
ensure a strong and conducive economic and financial systems.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Singapore carried out financial reforms through
shifting from regulation to supervision, exercising risk-focused
supervision and enhancing transparency while private sector
participation and multi-agency networking were encouraged.
</P>
<P>
Tan also said MAS will set up overseas promotion offices in New
York and London respectively in a bid to continue the momentum
toward broadening and deepening Singapore's financial sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
