<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algerian New Prime Minister Appointed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Algerian President Liamine
Zeroual Tuesday appointed National Assembly member Ismail Hamdani
as New Prime Minister to replace Ahmed Ouyahia who has resigned.
</P>
<P>
According to well-informed sources, Hamdani is expected to
present his list of cabinet ministers to President Zeroual early
next week.
</P>
<P>
Daily "Al Khabar" quotes the official sources as saying that
the new cabinet will be composed of the previous ruling coalition
with some changes.
</P>
<P>
The reports added that Ouyahia's resignation came immediately
after the National People's Assembly strongly criticized his
government's failure to implement the policy it had submitted to
the legislative assembly last year.
</P>
<P>
Ouyahia was appointed as Prime Minister in December, 1995 after
his National Democratic Rally won 155 seats in the 380-member
parliament in the elections.
</P>
<P>
He was believed as a close associate of Zeroual in implementing
the policies of economic reforms and suppressing terrorist groups
in the past years.
</P>
<P>
The sources further stated that the new government will present
before the end of December its plan of action to parliament for
endorsement. It will then undertake its responsibilities for just
four months, as its term of office will automatically terminate
upon the election of a new president in April.
</P>
<P>
The sources point out that the new government program focuses
on preparations for the presidential elections besides discharging
public affairs and preparing for the convocation of a scheduled
summit conference of the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
According to the Algerian news agency, Ismail Hamdani was born
on March 11, 1930 at Bordj Bou Arreridj located some 246 kilometers
southeast of the Algerian capital city of Algiers.
</P>
<P>
He studied law and English language and graduated from
Cambridge University.
</P>
<P>
As member of the civil organization of the National Liberation
Front, he obtained the national order of merit, and had also been
decorated by Mauritania, Tunisia and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
During his long professional career as civil servant, Hamdani
occupied the posts of diplomatic counselor of former president
Hou ari Boumedienne, secretary general of the government, secretary
general of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, and Ambassador to a
number of European states.
</P>
<P>
Hamdani had also served as chairman of the Algerian society for
international relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polling Industry Benefits Ordinary Chinese Citizens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Zhou Baolan, a beauty
consultant working for a Beijing cosmetics company, pays close
attention to market surveys conducted by the local media.
</P>
<P>
"Surveys provide valuable information related to popular
products. I'm convinced that surveys are much more reliable than
advertisements." said Zhou.
</P>
<P>
She said clients with higher education levels are more likely
to monitor market surveys.
</P>
<P>
Zhou's comments are substantiated by the fact that the number
of ordinary citizens exhibiting interest in statistics has
increased significantly over the past five years in line with
expanded media coverage.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Yue, chairman of the Horizon Market survey Co., said that
ordinary Chinese citizens used to depend simply on intuition
and experience, but have gradually learned to use statistics
when making consumption decisions.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China's polling industry has maintained
an annual growth rate of over 100 percent since 1985.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, Close to 800 of the 2,000 polling agencies
in place by the end of 1997 conducted market surveys.
</P>
<P>
Over half of companies operated by government institutions,
multinational companies and branches of the media are based in big
cities of Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 700 nongovernmental companies account for
over 80 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
The highly efficient small companies enjoy a promising future
based on a stable market and low operating costs, Yuan said.
</P>
<P>
Various international polling organizations, including Gallup
and Land, are also bullish about the vast potential market in
China.
</P>
<P>
"China's market economy is moving towards globalization. The
current situation leaves something to be desired, but I firmly
believe the industry's prospects will improve along with the
deepening of reform," according to Fang Xiaoguang, vice-chairman
of Gallup (China). 
</P>
</TEXT>
