<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Restructures Futures Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- China has basically fulfilled
this year's targets for regulating the futures market, and will
continue to reduce excessive speculation in order to ensure
further consolidation.
</P>
<P>
Mergers and closures of China's futures exchanges, the focus of
1998 reform, has basically been completed and the number of
exchanges will be reduced from 14 to three in 1999, according to
official with China Securities Regulatory Commission (CSRC), the
nation's securities watchdog.
</P>
<P>
Three futures exchanges -- Shanghai, Zhengzhou and Dalian --
will continue operations.
</P>
<P>
The number of commodities traded on related markets will be
slashed from 35 to 12 and the guarantee margin will be raised from
five percent to ten percent, according to reform plans.
</P>
<P>
China launched futures markets in the early 1990s, with related
markets experiencing rapid development due to the absence of a
complete legal framework. The number of exchanges hit a peak of
60, with the number of commodities traded falling just short of 50.
</P>
<P>
The rampant speculation which accompanied rapid and poorly
regulated development pushed the prices of some futures contracts
to irrational levels and contributed to runaway inflation in 1993
and 1994 by driving prices on spot markets.
</P>
<P>
Related events prompted the government to introduce drastic
measures to regulate the market, with related efforts gradually
reducing the number of exchanges and commodity items to the
current level.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that China will focus on improving the legal
framework governing the futures market, standardizing operations
of futures exchanges and restructuring brokerages.
</P>
<P>
The prolonged sluggishness of markets has forced many futures
brokerages to close, with the number of firms dropping from a high
of over 1,000 to only 200. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
