<HEADLINE> Problems in South Asia Can Be Solved Through Economic Ties: Gujral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Former Indian prime minister
I. K. Gujral said Tuesday that most of the problems facing the
South Asian countries can be effectively resolved through
accelerated economic ties and setting up of free trade zones in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a seminar on "Indo-Pak Media Dialogue" organized by
the National Media Center here, Gujral said that economics and not
politics should be the guiding force behind the policies of India,
Pakistan and other countries in the region as everyone would gain
from cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"There is a high desirability for free trade zones in the
sub-continent which would not only facilitate economic activities
among countries but also lead to increased mobility of people and
interaction among them," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the problems in the region including Kashmir issue
would be solved with trade activities, industrial tie-up and
investment beyond borders which would melt away growing mistrust,"
he further said.
</P>
<P>
Transformation in the region would not be possible without free
trade and spread of education. Right to education itself would
play a key role in sorting out most of the problems, he said.
</P>
