<HEADLINE> China Welcomes Foreign Help For Flood Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- China now has a considerable
market for advanced water technology and equipment which it will
need to combat any future problems, Zhang Chunyuan, vice minister
of China's water resources said here today.
</P>
<P>
Following the worst flooding in 40 years this summer, which
devastated large tracts of the country, Chinese water experts are
keen to exchange ideas with their foreign counterparts on how to
improve their technology and equipment when they meet up during
next year's 'Water Expo China '99'.
</P>
<P>
Officials and technicians from nearly 20 countries, including
Germany, India, Australia and the Netherlands, are expected to
attend the expo according to Zhang who announced details of the
event today.
</P>
<P>
He added that the two months of flooding this summer had cost
the country 239.7 billion yuan in direct economic losses and had
revealed the inherent weaknesses in the country's water resources
technologies.
</P>
<P>
"China has increased spending on water conservation and will
actively use modern technology and equipment for flood defense
works, flood monitoring and forecasting, emergency management,
preventing disasters, waste water purification and in numerous
other fields," he said.
</P>
<P>
And he revealed that professional teams involved in water
projects will be encouraged to attend the show, which will take
place in November next year.
</P>
<P>
Li Changfan, vice chairman of the expo's organizing
committee, who is also a water ministry official, announced that
China is reviewing its action plan for water conservation which
will allow more projects to be launched over the coming years.
</P>
<P>
"This new plan should be ready by November next year in time
for the expo and demonstrates China's huge need for international
cooperation in terms of handling its water resources." he added.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
