<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Significant Progress Made in Three-Way Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The stalemate in the
implementation of the Wye peace accord failed to be broken at a
Tuesday summit of U.S. President Bill Clinton, Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority
Chairman Yasser Arafat
</P>
<P>
After the 90-minute meeting at the Erez border crossing, the
three leaders failed to hold a joint conference, with Arafat
walking away without addressing and Netanyahu intransigently
sticking to his previous position. Clinton was the only one to
describe the three-way summit as "very good."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the Palestinian-Israeli peace accord has been got
back on track. But he added there are still several issues to be
worked out and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will return
to the region soon for further talks.
</P>
<P>
Clinton began a three-day visit to Israel and the Palestinian
self-rule areas Saturday night at a time when Israel and the PNA
ran into a dispute over the release of Palestinian prisoners,
which has incurred violent clashes and the Israeli suspension of
the implementation of the Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
The summit is the first meeting of the three leaders since late
October when they hammered out the the Wye Plantation agreement
near Washington.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Israel should phase out its troops from
another 13 percent of the West Bank within three months in return
for tougher Palestinian actions on Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also provides that Israel releases 750
Palestinian prisoners by the end of January, 1999. Last month, 250
of them were freed, but most were common criminals, not political
prisoners demanded by the Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians urged more release of political prisoners, but
Netanyahu holds that he will not free those who killed Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Violent clashes erupted as a result between Palestinian
protesters and Israeli soldiers in the West Bank, killing two
Palestinian youths and injuring 150 others.
</P>
<P>
Under the widespread clashes which were blamed on the PNA by
Israel and pressure from the hardliners in his coalition,
Netanyahu ordered to suspend further troop withdrawal .
</P>
<P>
He insisted there will be no further redeployment until the
Palestinians fulfill all their obligations. He also vowed not to
bow to external pressures to make concessions.
</P>
<P>
But Clinton said the two sides has agreed to set up a formal
channel to discuss the prisoner issue.
</P>
<P>
Asked if Israel will go ahead with the second-stage troop
withdrawal under the Wye agreement as scheduled Friday, Clinton
said he hopes Israel can carry out the accord in line with the
timetable but stressed that "a lot of issues need to be worked
out."
</P>
<P>
In related development, Israeli media reported before the
summit that the Palestinian Prisoners Association has decided to
continue to organize protests if the issue is not resolved.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Council Monday revoked the clauses in
the Palestinian national charter calling for the destruction of
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Despite terming the nullification of anti-Israel clauses "an
important step," Netanyahu still listed a series of demands which
he said the Palestinians have to meet before any further Israeli
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
These demands included the halt of anti-Israeli incitement, the
collection of illegal weapons, the arrest of Palestinian
terrorists and a public announcement by Arafat that he will not
declare a Palestinian state unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
According to Clinton, several steering committees on these
issues have been established at the meeting and they will meet
later Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Local observers said it seemed highly unlikely that Netanyahu,
who faces a critical no-confidence motion in the parliament next
week, will carry out the second stage of withdrawals Friday to
anger the hardliners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
