<HEADLINE> Moderate Rise in Overseas Investment in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Actual overseas investment in
China between January and November this year rose 2.66 percent
compared to the same period last year, according to figures
released by the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation
(MOFTEC) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The amount of overseas investment in the first 11 months
of 1998 reached 41.07 billion U.S. dollars, an increase of 963
million U.S. dollars, despite a decrease in the volume of
contractual investment.
</P>
<P>
Affected by the Asian financial crisis this year, the number of
overseas-invested ventures established between January and
November dropped to 17,857, down 4.22 percent from the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
The volume of contractual investment involved declined 0.18
percent, according to MOFTEC.
</P>
<P>
The largest overseas investor in that period continued to be
Hong Kong, which recorded a contractual investment volume of
14.09 billion U.S. dollars, accounting for 32.06 percent of the
total. Its actual investment reached 17.15 billion U.S. dollars,
representing 41.76 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Other major investors include Taiwan, Japan, the United States
and the Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
According to MOFTEC there are now 322,732 overseas-funded
ventures in China; the first set up in April 1980. Their
contractual investment volume has topped 565.17 billion
U.S. dollars, and the actual volume has reached 262.94 billion
U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
