<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Accelerates Urbanization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official said
today that the development of city groups, proliferation of small
cities and towns, and steady perfection of urban functions have
combined to accelerate the process of China's urbanization.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Minister of Construction Ye Rutang noted that vigorous
local economic growth has led to the emergence of city groups
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
He noted that most groups are concentrated in the Yangtze and
Pearl river deltas, as well as on the Liaoning Peninsula and in
the Beijing-Tianjin-Tangshan area.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics show that China has established 666 cities,
including 32 cities with populations of over one million people
each. Forty-three cities have population ranging from 500,000 to
one million, 192 medium-sized cities with a population of 200,000
to 500,000 and 399 small cities with less than 200,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Ye noted that rapid urbanization has also at least to a
certain degree improved the uneven distribution of cities between
eastern and western China. The former region accounts for 44
percent and the latter 19 percent the total number of cities.
</P>
<P>
He said the fact that even more cities are under development in
the vast western region will help to improve economic development
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The steady expansion of urbanization has been accompanied by
the strong growth of public facilities in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the urban gas usage rate has jumped to 60
percent, with the coverage of green space in cities standing
at 22.4 percent. In addition, the per capita living space for
urban residents has jumped to 7.9 square meters.
</P>
<P>
Ye predicted that China will have 800 cities by the year 2000,
with the number of small towns rising to over 60,000. He said
related growth will raise urbanization to an even more rational
level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
