<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hazardous Wastes Dumped Near Sihanoukville, Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 15 (Xinhua) -- About 3,000 tons of wastes
dumped about 15 km on the outskirts of Sihanoukville were
suspected to contain chemicals hazardous to health.
</P>
<P>
So far, the hazardous wastes had already caused at least three
villagers dead. A pollution-control official also said he had
heard reports of villagers who had scavenged the area suffering
from skin rashes, diarrhea and other symptoms.
</P>
<P>
It was suspected the wastes contain some heavy metals such as
mercury, zinc, chrome or lead that could seriously affect human
health.
</P>
<P>
The wastes were reportedly imported from overseas and dumped
behind a district military police post on the outskirts of
Sihanoukville which is an important watershed and near the Ream
National Park.
</P>
<P>
Environment Minister Mok Mareth called for a parliamentary
investigation and pledged to take the offenders to court.
</P>
<P>
"We will investigate who authorized the import of toxic waste
into Cambodia in this remote area," Mok Mareth said Sunday. "Who
authorized this should be punished. The import of toxic waste is
prohibited in the country."
</P>
<P>
According to the Cambodia Daily, the wastes were shipped in 100
kilogram polyester bags labeled as originating from a plastics
company in Taiwan. The customs documents indicated the shipment
was of construction wastes.
</P>
<P>
"But if it is just construction waste, why spend all the money
for transportation to Cambodia?" Heng Nareth, deputy director of
Cambodia's pollution control department, asked.
</P>
<P>
"Cambodia is not going to become a dumping site for toxic
waste," Mok Mareth said. "If it becomes one, it will kill the
people of this generation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
