<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt Starts 45-Day Ceasefire With Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
set to declare a 45-day ceasefire with the rebel National
Democratic Front-Communist Party starting midnight Tuesday up to
January 20 next year.
</P>
<P>
Ronaldo Zamora, secretary of executive, told reporters of the
upcoming truce with the rebels following a meeting of the Office
of the President Executive Committee.
</P>
<P>
Orlando Mercado, secretary of defense, also made clear that the
ceasefire does not cover regular law enforcement activities and
security functions undertaken by the police and military to ensure
peace and order.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has yet to receive indications from the
National Democratic Front-Communist Party of the Philippines-New
People's Army that it will likewise declare a suspension of
offensive military operations.
</P>
<P>
"This is unilateral on the part of government in the spirit of
Christmas, upon the recommendation on the part of the Chief of
Staff of the Armed Forces," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the ceasefire, the government will suspend
offensive military operations against the party and all its
factions.
</P>
<P>
Mercado confirmed an earlier statement by National Security
Adviser Alexander Aguirre that there is no need for a separate
ceasefire with the Moro Islamic Liberation Front in Mindanao
because of an existing truce agreement with the rebel group.
</P>
</TEXT>
