<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Imposes Traffic Restriction Against Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Traffic police in Tehran on
Tuesday announced an emergency traffic restriction as part of
efforts to reduce the alarming air pollution in the Iranian
capital.
</P>
<P>
The restriction in force from 6:00 a.m. to 10:00 p.m. will
take effect from Wednesday until further notice, the Islamic
Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the restriction, except Friday, private cars with
even number plates must travel on even days and odd number plates
on odd days.
</P>
<P>
As of Wednesday morning, the plate number of vehicles violating
the new regulations will be registered and the violators will be
deprived of future concessions by traffic department.
</P>
<P>
All private cars and motorcycles which emit exhaust fumes due
to malfunction will be stopped and fined, the announcement said.
</P>
<P>
The announcement also called on all organizations, ministries
and military forces to abide by the new regulations to ward off
further damage.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after senior health officials warned of
"alarming" air pollution in the city, which had led to the death
of some patients with heart and respiratory problems.
</P>
<P>
The air pollution, which befell Tehran days ago due to the
phenomenon of air reversion in winter, has exacerbated for lack of
wind and precipitation, plus the pollutants released by the huge
fleet of battered automobiles.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that 71.2 percent of the air pollution in Tehran
is created by motor vehicles, most of which are old and not
equipped with smog-control devices.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Deputy Health Minister Ali Bar Sayari said on Monday
that dangerous noxious gases have increased ten folds in Tehran
over the past four days as a result of stable weather and air
reversion.
</P>
<P>
He also said the pollution has reached an alarming level as
the volume of carbon monoxide in air has risen to 18 PPM, twice
the standard volume.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Mohammad Farhadi Monday urged people to avoid
"unnecessary trips" and called on the elderly, children and those
suffering from allergies to remain at home.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, all elementary, secondary and high schools and
some universities in Tehran, Shahr Rey and Shemiranat, the three
major cities of Tehran province, were closed down upon a
recommendation made by the Environment Protection Organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
