<HEADLINE> Philippine Official Explains Agreement on Marcos Deposits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
Tuesday dismissed claims that the move to invest the Marcos
deposits held in escrow at the Philippine National Bank (PNB)
would violate an agreement signed by the Philippine and Swiss
governments.
</P>
<P>
In an ambush interview here, Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora
said that the escrow agreement allows the government, together
with the foundations under which the funds were originally
deposited in Swiss banks, to put the money into higher yielding
investments.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, he said, the 570 million U.S. dollars of
Marcos assets were allowed to be transferred to PNB.
</P>
<P>
But earlier, Rod Domingo, one of the lawyers of the 10,000
human rights victims, who won a 2.35-billion-dollar judgment in a
class-action suit against the Marcoses in Hawaii, warned that the
government may violate two diplomatic notes, should it push
through with its plan to dispose of the Marcos Swiss deposits.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said that under the signed escrow, "the Philippine
government together with the foundations, can put them (Marcos
Swiss deposits) in better yielding fund." 
</P>
</TEXT>
