<HEADLINE> Another Group of Iraqi POWs to Return Home Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 15 (xinhua) -- A new batch of Iraqi prisoners
of war (POWs) and those Missing in actions (MIAs) will return to
Iraq from Iran on Wednesday under the latest agreement between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Babil daily, published on Tuesday said the State Company
for Transport had prepared first-class buses to transport the
POWs and MIAs.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Yahya al-Ani, General-Director of the
company, as saying that the company will transport the POWs in
groups from al-Muntheriyah border point to their home towns.
</P>
<P>
Iraq recently expressed optimism for closing the file of POWs
and MIAs with Iran forever as the latest negotiations with Iran in
Tehran proved successful and fruitful.
</P>
<P>
Nabd Al-Shabab weekly quoted an unnamed official of Iraqi
Foreign Ministry as saying that Iraq is more optimistic now than
any other time before towards the issue of POWs and MIAs.
</P>
<P>
Under the latest agreement, Iran will release all the remaining
registered and unregistered Iraqi POWs and MIAs, said the
official.
</P>
<P>
He said that the latest negotiations with Iran was franker and
clearer than before. "This frankness and clearness will accelerate
the process of closing the humanitarian file forever."
</P>
<P>
The official said that Iran will release the first group of
registered and unregistered POWs on Wednesday without giving exact
number, but specified that the remaining MIAs in both countries
will be announced.
</P>
<P>
He said the two countries will continue their discussions and
will display the latest findings in the future meeting of the
joint Iraqi-Iranian Committee for POWs.
</P>
<P>
The POW issue left over by the eight-year Iran-Iraq war which ended
in 1988, has been a thorny problem for the two countries to restore
bilateral relations for years. Tens of thousands of military
personnel from each sides were captured during the war and most of
them had been released. 
</P>
</TEXT>
