<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> B d c 2390 China-Flu-Epidemic Flu Epidemic Sweeps Northern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 15 (Xinhua) -- A virulent strain of flu has
swept northern China in the last seven days with hospitals and
clinics in Beijing and other cities packed with sufferers
complaining of high fevers and breathing difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-Japanese Friendship Hospital reported four-fold
increases of patients as the particularly vicious A-type virus,
identified by doctors as H3N2, has China's northern population in
its grip.
</P>
<P>
Last year a B-type strain of flu ran rampant at exactly the
same time according to Guo Yuanji, director of China's National
Influenza Center (NIC).
</P>
<P>
"However, compared with the B type, H3N2 can be much more
harmful," Guo said, while also predicting that the week long
outbreak may last ten more days.
</P>
<P>
"Northern China has entered the peak season for its usual bouts
of influenza epidemics," he added.
</P>
<P>
Flu experts also blamed the outbreak on recent abrupt climatic
changes in northern China.
</P>
<P>
"It's easy to catch colds since the temperature often drops
quite quickly below zero," said He Xiong, who is in charge of
influenza detection at the Beijing Epidemic Prevention Station.
</P>
<P>
China's mass media has made valiant efforts to pass on advice
from experts about people keeping away from public places and has
advised them to ventilate rooms, particularly for the elderly,
children and patients with heart problems and chronic illnesses.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Guo and his colleagues are trying to find out
if the H3N2 strain is a new mutation, which happens frequently
with the flu virus making preventive measures more difficult
than usual.
</P>
<P>
China has been vulnerable to flu for centuries and it is
claimed that the 'bug' actually originated there. Now, both
Chinese and foreign medical experts are predicting that a
large-scale influenza epidemic will occur worldwide before the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"We've received epidemic reports from provinces in northeastern
and northwestern regions of China in the last few days, which are
similar to the situation here in Beijing," Guo added.
</P>
<P>
There is no easily available flu vaccine in China so far but
Guo Yuanji said that the NIC is working closely with the Lanzhou
Biological Research Institute in an attempt to develop the
country's first flu vaccine, which he hopes will prevent another
epidemic next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
