<HEADLINE> Sound Sino-US Ties Conductive to Both, FM Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- As China and the United States
prepare to mark the 20th anniversary of opening diplomatic
relations, China has stressed it is ready to work jointly with the
U.S. to maintain the relations in a healthy and stable manner well
into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Sun Yuxi made the remark at
a routine press conference today.
</P>
<P>
The actual anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic ties
between the two countries falls on January 1st next year. Sun
commented that over the past two decades bilateral ties have
witnessed progress despite some turns and twists.
</P>
<P>
"Promoting friendly, cooperative and mutually beneficial
Sino-US relations is the common aspiration of our two peoples, and
is in the fundamental interests of both, as well as being
conductive to peace, stability and prosperity in the Asia-Pacific
region and the world at large," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sun recalled how Chinese President Jiang Zemin and
U.S. President Bill Clinton have paid successful reciprocal state
visits and that both heads of state have agreed to build up a
constructive strategic partnership, giving an impetus to Sino-US
relations and taking them into a new phase.
</P>
<P>
"The course of the development of the relations between the two
countries demonstrates that the principles set forth in the three
Sino-US joint communiques are the foundation of bilateral
relations," he commented, adding that adherence to the three
communiques "has been and will be the essential guarantee for the
healthy and steady development of Sino-US ties."
</P>
<P>
Sun reiterated that China is willing to make joint efforts with
the U.S. for the continued development of such ties and hoped the
two sides could take a strategic and long-term prospective.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides should soundly look at the matters over which they
do not agree, in particular the Taiwan issue, so as to expand
common ground and develop cooperation," he said. 
</P>
