<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Held with 58 Drug Capsules in Stomach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 15 (Xinhua) -- A Tanzanian man with 58
capsules of heroin in the stomach has been arrested by the police
at the Dar es Salaam International Airport.
</P>
<P>
Press reports said here Tuesday that Omary Said, 32, a
resident of Dar es Salaam, was suspected to be in unlawful
possession of a forged passport of Botswana upon his arrival from
Pakistan last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He was taken to a local hospital for X-ray examination and the
heroine packets were found in his stomach.
</P>
<P>
"He later discharged the heroin, worth 5.8 million Shillings
(some 8,600 U.S. Dollars) at street value, through the rectum,"
the Commander of the Anti-Drugs Unit was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Esaka Mugasa said the suspect held a passport No. 215363 of
Botswana showing that his name was Kalaba Mphutshinyane born in
1966 at Mogojogojwe, Botswana.
</P>
<P>
"He pretended that he did not speak Kiswahili language until
he was forced to concede that he is a Tanzanian," the Commander
said, adding, "the International Police (Interpol) is
investigating its legality."
</P>
<P>
Mugasa said the man Said left Dar es Salaam for Pakistan early
this month and was believed to collect the drugs in Karachi.
</P>
<P>
The convict, who is still in hospital for observation under
police monitoring, will be brought to court soon.
</P>
<P>
The Anti-Drug Unit chief called upon the public to inform the
police of any suspected possession of illicit drugs. 
</P>
