<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF to Disburse Eighth Loan to S. Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) Tuesday approved disbursement of its eighth loan of one
billion U.S. dollars to South Korea, the Ministry of Finance and
Economy said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF made the approval after its fourth quarter policy
consultation with South Korea and the eighth loan will reach the
central Bank Korea Wednesday, said the ministry.
</P>
<P>
With the latest IMF disbursement, South Korea will have drawn
19 billion dollars, or 90.5 percent of the IMF's bailout loan last
December.
</P>
<P>
South Korea signed an agreement with the IMF last December for
a rescue loan of 58 billion dollars after it was gripped by
corporate bankruptcies and bad loans of financial institutions in
late 1997. Out of the 58 billion dollars, some 22 billion dollar
are from the IMF while others from other international financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is expected to receive one billion dollars from the
IMF next year and another one billion dollars in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Alassane Quattara, IMF deputy managing director, said South
Korean economy will return to positive growth next year.
</P>
<P>
"South Korea's decision last week to start repaying money
borrowed from the IMF was a reassuring signal to the international
community that the country was emerging out of its crisis," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The severe downturn in output has begun to abate, and the
Korean won remains stable and interest rates are at pre-crisis
levels," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, the IMF official cautioned that consumer and investor
confidence remains weak and the speed of recovery will depend to a
great degree on the progress of corporate and financial
restructuring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
