<HEADLINE> 41 Out of 64 Districts Arsenic-Affected in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Forty-one out of Bangladesh's 64
districts have been identified as arsenic affected, which is
posing a serious health hazard to 62 percent of the total
population of 127 million, The New Nation daily newspaper reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Dhaka Community Hospital (DCH) authority disclosed this
Monday in Dhaka at a two-day workshop on "Arsenic Problem and
Water Resources Management in Bangladesh."
</P>
<P>
The DCH authority said that they identified 20 districts as
severe arsenic affected after conducting emergency arsenic
mitigation program.
</P>
<P>
Ground water in many parts of the country was contaminated with
arsenic which occurs naturally in alluvial and deltaic sediments
posing a serious water hazard as ground water is the primary
source of drinking water in Bangladesh, speakers pointed out at
the workshop.
</P>
<P>
The presence of arsenic has been confirmed in 41 districts of
the country though sample surveys conducted by the DCH in 60 out
of 64 districts.
</P>
<P>
Proper watershed management, utilization of huge number of
water bodies with people's participation and rain water harvesting
are needed, according to the speakers.
</P>
<P>
Safe water, nutritious food and physical exercise are the only
medicines for chronic arsenic toxicity at present, they pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
Pure water must be available to the Bangladeshi people, all
data on the catastrophe must be recorded and shared with others
coping with the problem in order to ensure a rapid solution and
prevent a repetition of the catastrophe, they stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
