<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unit Trust Sees Net Outflows of US$104M in First 10 Months 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Investment
Funds Association (HKIFA) announced Tuesday that the unit
trust industry registered net outflows of 103.99 million U.S.
dollars between January and October 1998.
</P>
<P>
Amongst the 14 fund sectors, the six Asian sectors registered
aggregate net outflows of 454.80 million U.S. dollars, HKIFA
Chairman Desmond Chan told a press conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Asia-Pacific Regional (excluding Japan, including Hong
Kong) funds and Japanese equity funds registered the highest
outflows, Chan said. They respectively registered net outflows of
143.27 million U.S. dollars and 100.50 million U.S. dollars in the
10-month period.
</P>
<P>
The remaining four Asian sectors also saw net outflows, though
the level of outflows was relatively lower. Out of the four
sectors, Hong Kong equities funds witnessed the heaviest outflows,
at 89.85 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
On reasons behind the massive outflows from Asian funds, Chan
said the sharp volatilities experienced by the Asian markets in
the financial maelstrom, as well as concerns over the short and
medium-term outlook of the regional economies have spurred
investors to shun Asian-related products.
</P>
<P>
The sectors that investors had been turning to were European
equities funds, bond funds and cash funds, Chan said.
</P>
<P>
The traditional safe haven sector -- cash funds attracted net
inflows of 80.51 million U.S. dollars in the 10-month period, Chan
said.
</P>
<P>
During the period, cash funds, European equities funds and bond
funds were the three leading sectors in gross inflows, attracting
aggregate gross inflows of 1.716 billion U.S. dollars, accounting
for 58 percent of the industry total, Chan said.
</P>
<P>
On the outlook of sales, Chan said that as the conditions in
Asia stabilize, investors have gradually increased their holdings
in Asia.
</P>
<P>
However, it is likely that the approach to Asia would continue
to be one of selective buying, with investors focusing on markets
that have more positive signs of recovery.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in the next few months, bond and cash products would
probably remain as the mainstay of a typical diversified
portfolio, Chan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0170 </DOCNO>
