<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Slightly Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar spent
in the doldrums Tuesday, pegged on either side by weak commodity
prices and U.S. stock market concerns about the impending
impeachment of U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The local currency closed slightly higher after trading in a
tight range on the session.
</P>
<P>
"The Aussie will find it hard to rally too much with
commodities as weak as they are, but on the other side the market
is very concerned about U.S. markets and the impending impeachment
by the House of Reps," Rothschild &AMP; Sons senior manager Paul
Macarounas said.
</P>
<P>
The local currency, which finished at 62.05 U.S. cents from
61.85 late Monday, was also the victim of thin pre-Christmas
trading.
</P>
<P>
"It is tough this time of the year because liquidity does dry
out a bit," Macarounas said.
</P>
<P>
He said Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) governor Ian
Macfarlane's testimony to the House of Representatives Standing
Committee on Financial Institutions and Public Administration
offered little spark for the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
"Underlying everything, commodities are still ruling the roost
and concerns about U.S. markets and the impending impeachment are
probably acting on the other side of that, keeping the Aussie from
falling too far away," he said.
</P>
<P>
Anxiety in the White House increased as more Republicans said
they would vote to impeach Clinton and three Republican leaders
called for his resignation.
</P>
<P>
The Australian currency was buying 72.48 Japanese yen from
71.84 and 1.0272 German marks from 1.0182. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
