<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Subsidizes Meetings of Separated Families </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government
Tuesday announced that South Koreans who have kin in the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) will receive
financial support from the government if they meet their divided
relatives or confirm their whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Unification Minister Kang In-duk Tuesday issued a
decree on financial support for separated families, which takes
effect immediately.
</P>
<P>
Under the decree, a separated family will each receive 400,000
won (350 U.S. dollars) when they confirm where their kin live in
the DPRK or will receive 800,000 won (700 U.S. dollars) after it
meets separated relatives for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the decree also provides that families currently
receiving government subsidies and families whose kin were
prisoners of war in the DPRK will each receive 1,600,000 won
(1,400 U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
