<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Political Parties Registered in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The Independent National
Electoral Commission (INEC) of Nigeria has registered three
political parties out of nine given provisional registration to
contest the December 5 local council elections.
</P>
<P>
Those given final registration are the People's Democratic
Party (PDP), All People's Party (APP) and Alliance for Democracy
(AD), according to a New Nigerian report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
INEC Chairman Justice Ephraim Akpata was quoted as saying in
capital Abuja Monday that the three parties are qualified to
contest the remaining elections under the transition to civil
rule program.
</P>
<P>
According to him, AD scored five percent and above of total
votes cast in 14 states including the Federal Capital Territory
(FCT) and won 100 chairmanship positions and 1,071 councillorship
seats.
</P>
<P>
The APP scored five percent votes and above in 36 states
including FCT with 188 chairmanship position and 2,589
councillorship seats.
</P>
<P>
The PDP had five percent and above in 36 states and FCT with
459 chairmanship positions and 4,650 councillorship seats.
</P>
<P>
Justice Akpata said that by the results, the APP and the PDP
fulfilled the conditions for final registration as political
parties as stipulated in the guidelines for registration of
political parties.
</P>
<P>
He explained that while all the other parties did not obtain
up to 5 percent of the total votes cast in at least 24 states,
one of them will be granted final registration along with the PDP
and APP by virtue of a provision of the guidelines.
</P>
<P>
The INEC chairman Monday announced the guidelines for the
January 9 governorship elections, saying that there will be a
governor elected for each of all 36 states while a member will be
elected into the House of Assembly from each of the state
constituencies.
</P>
<P>
The three registered political parties are expected to present
a list of candidates to the commission before December 23 and the
commission shall in turn deliver to the parties a list of those
qualified and disqualified from contesting the election before
December 31.
</P>
<P>
The mode of voting shall be the same as was adopted at the
last local government elections, that is by Open Secret Ballot,
and the voting shall take place on the same day and at the same
time throughout the country, the chairman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
