<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin Votes for Deputies to District People's Congress (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In accordance with the nation's laws, various levels of local
people's congresses are instituted as official organs of state
power.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese people are able to directly elect deputies to the
people's congresses in districts or counties, the highest level at
which such elections are held at the present time.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu Rongji completed his ballot paper with a special
calligraphy writing brush and as a result had to wait until the
ink was dry to cast his vote.
</P>
<P>
"Voting for deputies to the district people's congress is my
right as well as my obligation," Zhu said, "Naturally, I supported
the candidate I voted for."
</P>
<P>
Li Ruihuan, Hu Jintao, Wei Jianxing and Li Lanqing, all members
of the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the Central
Committee of the Chinese Communist Party, and other Party and
state leaders voted in today's election or mandated others to do
it on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
A total of 4,403 deputies to district or county people's
congresses must have been chosen by the end of this year. Electors
in the ten districts in Beijing were able to vote between eight
a.m. and midnight today.
</P>
<P>
Wang Changlian, head of Xicheng District, said, "The Party and
state leaders are all part of the electorate in my district."
</P>
<P>
"Their participation in this local voting system indicates the
progress of the country's legal and democratic system," Wang added.
</P>
<P>
Most of the deputies to district or county people's congresses
throughout the rest of the country have already been elected.
</P>
</TEXT>
