<HEADLINE> No Plan to Replace S. Africa National Anthem: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 15 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki has said that there is no plan to change
the current national anthem.
</P>
<P>
Local daily Sowetan quoted Mbeki as saying that despite his
enthusiastic reception of a proposed new national anthem sung
entirely in English, there was no decision to replace the current
hybrid of the African classic, God bless Africa.
</P>
<P>
The newly proposed South African national anthem, which calls
on South Africans to unite and build one rainbow nation, was
apparently given a "thumbs up" by Mbeki during its recording in
Cape Town at the weekend, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the song, all South Africans must "strive to keep
the virtues of justice, peace and freedom. No culture, creed or
custom should divide them".
</P>
<P>
Mbeki was quoted as having said that the song "pointed the way
forward for ourselves as a country".
</P>
<P>
However, in a statement Monday, Mbeki's office said there was
no decision from the government to replace the current anthem.
</P>
<P>
The current South African national anthem sung in both Nguni
and Afrikaans was adopted after the 1994 election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
