<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Leaders Call for Measures for Economic Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Southeast Asian leaders,
beginning a two-day summit here Tuesday, called for measures to
restore the region's economy to its previous glory.
</P>
<P>
In a keynote speech at the opening session Tuesday, Vietnamese
Prime Minister Phan Van Khai, who is also chairman of the summit,
expressed the hope that the economic turmoil "would give us
valuable lessons to design a system for warning, preventing and
handling untoward developments."
</P>
<P>
He also called for "practical economic, financial and monetary
measures" including those related to the establishment of the
ASEAN Free Trade Area and the ASEAN Investment Area, which he said
"will certainly create a synergy for us to quickly overcome the
crisis and move further forward."
</P>
<P>
The region covered by the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) used to be one of the fastest growing areas in the
world in the 1980s and 1990s before it was struck by a financial
crisis which wiped out much of the gains they had made in the
years and forced some countries such as Thailand and Indonesia to
seek help from the International Monetary Fund and other
organizations and countries.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian President B.J. Habibie noted in his statement that
the summit is being held "in the midst of a crisis that is putting
the resilience of our nations and that of our association to a
severe test."
</P>
<P>
Peace gave the ASEAN nations the chance to focus on economic
endeavors that resulted in three decades of sustained economic
growth, he said, adding that "peace will once more attend the
economic recovery of ASEAN," which groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos,
Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong said that in the
regional economic crisis, ASEAN economies have been badly damaged,
their wealth has been decimated and millions of people have lost
their jobs.
</P>
<P>
"But however dismal the immediate future looks, ASEAN cannot
lose its bearing and long-term optimism," he said.
</P>
<P>
He asked ASEAN countries to "reflect soberly on what ASEAN
means for each of us, how we can help each other to overcome our
economic challenges and how to position ASEAN for the rebound
which must come sooner or later."
</P>
<P>
He called for the acceleration of the pace in implementing
ASEAN's commitments to the ASEAN Free Trade Area, saying, "In the
midst of our economic difficulties, this will be a powerful signal
that we will keep our markets free, that we will remain plugged
into the global economy and that we are determined to move forward
with liberalization."
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada said ASEAN can start by
accelerating and deepening its tariff reduction program and
achieving early consolidation of the ASEAN Free Trade Area for its
consumers and export markets.
</P>
<P>
Poverty eradication was "of particular interest to the
Philippines," he said, adding that the human toll of the financial
crisis "demands urgent and concrete action."
</P>
<P>
"We must implement with fervor the ASEAN Action Plan on Rural
Development and Poverty Eradication," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai said the
present circumstances "also require us to be bold and demonstrate
our resolve to forge ahead even in the face of adversity." "This
is particularly true in so far as our economic cooperation is
concerned."
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for ASEAN "to generate the dynamics of
growth in the region and increase its global competitiveness."
</P>
<P>
"We must therefore strengthen our cooperation in the fields of
education, technology and the development of our infrastructure
network," he said. "More importantly, however, we must achieve
closer and deeper economic integration."
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said at the session
that in responding to the financial crisis, ASEAN countries have
instituted various macroeconomic measures and financial reforms.
</P>
<P>
He pledged to back initiatives aimed at strengthening regional
economic cooperation and consolidating the economic fundamentals
of ASEAN member countries and support greater economic integration
and the acceleration of the ASEAN Free Trade Area.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar leader Than Shwe expressed the confidence that ASEAN
countries will be able to overcome the present difficulties and
that "our region will again rise up to resume its rightly position
as the most economically dynamic region of the world."
</P>
<P>
Brunei Sultan Hassanal Bolkiah and Lao Prime Minister Sisavat
Keobounphan in their speeches also called for unity among ASEAN
members to overcome the current economic difficulties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Soldiers' Involvement in Killing S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho police Tuesday
confirmed that three South African farmers were shot dead by
members of the Lesotho Defense Force (LDF) in the rugged southern
district of Quthing on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Speaking from the capital of Maseru, Lesotho police spokesman
Sekoateng Serabele said police received a report of the incident
on Monday evening and visited the area Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Serabele disputed reports that the South Africans were on a
mission to retrieve stolen livestock, saying the men crossed the
border to steal livestock.
</P>
<P>
Serabele said he assumed the bodies of the three South
Africans were still in Lesotho. He was still awaiting reports
from police in the area and had no information on two South
Africans who were reportedly wounded in the incident.
</P>
<P>
Serabele said according to reports, a group of armed men from
Matatiele in Eastern Cape, South Africa, crossed into Lesotho on
Saturday night and raided a cattle post.
</P>
<P>
The men seized about 64 sheep and goats and drove them in the
direction of Matatiele, Serabele said.
</P>
<P>
Basotho villagers alerted members of the LDF who were on
patrol in the area.
</P>
<P>
The LDF patrol followed the alleged thieves and before they
left Lesotho territory there was an exchange of gunfire in which
the three South Africans were shot dead, Serabele said.
</P>
<P>
The LDF soliders captured the animals and returned them to
their owners.
</P>
<P>
Serabele said the rest of the group fled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
