<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue to Fall in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices in Tokyo fell for
the fourth straight trading day on Tuesday, stirred by the banking
sector's decline following the temporary nationalization of Nippon
Credit Bank (NCB), with the key Nikkei index once slipping below
14,000 for the first in over a month.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 100.43 points, or 0.71
percent, from Monday's close to end at 14,011.19.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, dropped 11.04 points or 1.00 percent to
1,089.27.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up to an estimated 410
million shares from Monday's 319.71 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Yasuda Trust Bank was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Concern is growing that the value of a bank share might become
zero suddenly after investors saw NCB shares were removed from the
stock market, and this heavily weighs on the banking sector, a
dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Bank shares faced strong selling pressure, while
export-oriented high-tech blue chips moved lower due to the
overnight tumble on Wall Street and the yen's recent surge against
the U.S. dollar, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers far exceeded
gainers 804 to 327, with 172 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
