<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expert: "Y2K Bug" Could Lead to Navigational Failure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The "millennium bug" of
computer could lead to navigational equipment failure as the
shipping and maritime industries are lagging considerably behind
worldwide efforts to eliminate the problem, a U.S. senior official
said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Central banks and telecommunications firms around the world had
made considerable progress in updating financial systems and the
aviation industry was beginning to move more aggressively, but the
shipping industry had "escaped attention," said John Koshinen,
chairman of President Bill Clinton's council on the millennium
problem.
</P>
<P>
He noted that 95 percent of all goods coming into the United
States arrived by sea.
</P>
<P>
Koshinen also urged specialists and officials, who are
participating in the first global conference on the 2000 computer
bug, to press their respective governments to deal the Y2K problem
in all fields, including shipping industry.
</P>
<P>
The Year 2000 problem -- also called Y2K and the millennium bug
-- occurs as some computer programs, especially older ones, may
fail when the date changes to 2000. Because they were written to
recognize only the last two digits of a year, such programs could
read the digits "00" as 1900 instead of 2000.
</P>
<P>
No one really knows what will happen at century's end, and
predictions vary wildly from financial instability to civil
disorder. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
