<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Insists Palestinian Compliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu insisted Tuesday that the Palestinians have to
fulfill their obligations in the recent land-for-peace deal before
Israel further carries out its pending troop withdrawal from the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference after a three-way summit with Visiting
U.S. President Bill Clinton and Palestinian National Authority
Chairman Yasser Arafat at the Erez border crossing, Netanyahu
reiterated his positions that Israel would not release Palestinian
prisoners who killed Israelis.
</P>
<P>
He also demanded that the Palestinians take measures to stop
incitement against Israel, collect illegal weapons and give up
plans to declare a Palestinian state unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
"There will be a speedy redeployment as soon as the
Palestinians fulfill all their obligations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said Israel would not bow to external pressures to
make concessions on its internal issues.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Jerusalem would remain undivided capital
of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Clinton told American reporters that the meeting was
"very good," and the peace process has been back on track.
</P>
<P>
He said that Israeli government has reconfirmed its commitment
to the pullout but that there were still several issues to be
worked out.
</P>
<P>
However, Israel media reported that no progress had been made.
Arafat left for Gaza without talking to reporters. 
</P>
