<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Reaffirms Water Commitments to Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel
Sharon reassured on Monday that Jordan that it remains committed
to water clauses in the peace treaty signed by the two countries
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Sharon sent an official clarification to Jordan on statements
by Israeli Agriculture Minister Rafael Eitan that his country
will re-examine waters deals signed with the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Sharon said in the letter that his country will stand by all
its commitments in the peace accord with Jordan and shall continue
cooperation with the kingdom on various issues, including water.
</P>
<P>
The letter, delivered to Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdul
Ilah Khatib by Israeli Ambassador to Jordan Oded Eran monday,
was apparently a response to Jordan's demand for an explanation
from the Israeli government on the Israeli Agriculture minister's
statements.
</P>
<P>
The peace treaty between the two countries guaranteed an 215
million cubic meters of water to Jordan a year through new dams, a
treatment plant and diversion projects.
</P>
<P>
However, of the total 215 million cubic meters promised by
Israel, Jordan is currently receiving only about 60 million cubic
meters, according to the Jordan Times.
</P>
<P>
Official figures showed that Jordan, with an annual
population growth rate of 3.5 percent, will need 1.2 billion
cubic meters of water per year between 1998 and 2000. The
kingdom's water resources will only amount to 960 million
cubic meters a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
