<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 09:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Rivals Agree to Facilitate Contact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Businessmen in a four-side
meeting to discuss a proposal for possible cooperation on the
divided Cyprus have agreed to facilitate contact between Greek and
Turkish Cypriots on the island.
</P>
<P>
The four sides, involving Turkey, Greece, Greek Cypriots and
Turkish Cypriots, voiced their stands in a statement issued at the
end of the two-day meeting Monday, local Daily News reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that "the participants reaffirmed their
desire for contact and cooperation to increase" steps to relax and
eventually lift all restrictions on the free movement of people,
goods and services, and the value of participation by members of
both communities in non-governmental international meetings.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which was held in Turkish largest city of Istanbul,
was the second of its kind in the 35 years. It was organized by
Columbia University's International Conflict Resolution Program
and the International Peace Research Institute of Oslo.
</P>
<P>
"I am encouraged by the spirit of what I have seen at this
meeting," said U.S. presidential envoy for Cyprus Richard
Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey
landed its troops and took over the northern third of the island
in the wake of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared a "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus" in 1983, which is only recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has been prodding the rival four sides to find a
peaceful solution to the Cyprus problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
