<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, December 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton at last
brought together Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat Tuesday
morning for a three-way summit at the Erez border Crossing between
Israel and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
The summit came less than one day after the Palestinians took a
decisive step on the peace process as hundreds of members of the
Palestine National Council (PNC) and other leadership bodies
convened and reaffirmed the annulment of anti-Israel provisions in
the Palestinian charter. Israel, which linked the holding of a
three-way summit with the outcome of the PNC meeting, welcomed the
PNC decision to revoke the anti-Israel charter.
(Clinton-Israel-Three-way Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The International Monetary Fund (IMF) decided on
Monday to disburse 1.022 billion U.S. dollars to South Korea under
a 21 billion dollars loan approved last year.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the decision, IMF Deputy Managing Director Alassane
Ouattara said in a statement that South Korea "continues to make
commendable progress in its efforts to achieve economic recovery."
However, he said, the confidence of both consumers and investors
remained weak as "there was little room for complacency."
(IMF-S.Korea-Loan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslav border guards killed 30 ethnic Albanian
fighters and injured 12 more who were trying to enter Kosovo from
Albania on Monday, said the Serbian information center in
Pristina, capital of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The ethnic Albanians, wearing uniforms of the outlawed Kosovo
Liberation Army, attempted to cross from neighboring Albania into
Kosovo before dawn. Intense gunfire was exchanged between the
guerrillas and the border guards, and large quantities of weapons
and supplies were seized after the shootout, the report said.
(Kosovo-Albanians-Fighting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentine President Carlos Menem vowed Monday
to reclaim his country's sovereignty over the Malvinas Islands
through dialogue with Britain.
</P>
<P>
Menem made the remarks at a graduation ceremony of the war
veterans studies center. Following the 1982 war between Argentina
and Britain over the disputed islands, also known as Falklands,
the two countries broke off diplomatic ties until 1990.
(Argentine-Malvinas-Sovereignty) 
</P>
