<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mini ECOWAS Summit to Discuss New Govt in Bissau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar has arrived in Lome, Togo, for a mini-summit
of the Economic Community for West African States (ECOWAS) on
Guinea Bissau on how to solve the crisis in that country.
</P>
<P>
The two-day summit which began Monday is expected to review
the progress in the implementation of the Abuja peace accord
signed on November 1 by the two parties to the seven-month crisis
in Guinea Bissau during the 21st ECOWAS Summit in Abuja,
according to a Nigerian Tribune report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Reliable sources said the Lome summit would concretize the
already existing peace accord and also evolve new measures to
move forward in peaceful settlement of the Bissau crisis.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace accord, the west African peace-keeping force of
ECOMOG will deploy a special task force in Guinea Bissau to take
over from Guinean and Senegalese troops which have been in that
country at the invitation of President Joao Bernardo Vieira.
</P>
<P>
A high-level ECOMOG team visited the country last month to
evaluate the logistic requirements for deploying an interposition
force in that country.
</P>
<P>
Four west African countries of Niger, Togo, Benin and Gambia
have pledged a total of 1,450 troops for the peace-keeping mission
in Guinea Bissau.
</P>
<P>
The peace accord also provides that a government of national
unity will be formed soon in the country and presidential
elections be held no later than March 1999.
</P>
<P>
Former Chief of Army Staff General Ansumane Mane led a
rebellion against President Vieira in June after he was sacked by
the latter for alleged involvement of senior army officers in
arms smuggling.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reached a cease-fire agreement in August after
negotiations brokered by ECOWAS and the Community of
Portuguese-Speaking Countries and reaffirmed the agreement on
November 1 in Nigeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
