<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan Steps Up Battle To Save Coral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Excessive coral mining by
fishermen around south China's tropical island of Hainan has
destroyed over 50 percent of the region's fragile reefs since the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics more than 20,000 hectares have
been wiped out and now in a bid to prevent further loss the
provincial government has banned the mining of coral reefs in its
waters.
</P>
<P>
It has also forbidden the sale or distribution of coral
by-products, such as lime, and introduced penalties for those who
transgress.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 400 varieties of coral reefs along the
Hainan coastlines, and more than 600 small islands in the South
China Sea are made up of coral.
</P>
<P>
Marine experts point out that waters rich in coral reefs are
vital to the stability of the sea's ecology and they also act as
barriers to prevent flooding of coastal areas by dispersing heavy
waves, as well as helping to keep sea-water clean.
</P>
<P>
A recent report released by the Nairobi-based World Research
Institute warns that coastal development, overfishing and
pollution, as a result of both land and marine based activities,
are threatening the future of nearly 60 percent of the world's
coral reefs.
</P>
<P>
Reefs occupy less than 0.25 percent of the earth's total
marine environment, yet they are home to more than half of all
known marine species, the report reveals.
</P>
<P>
It also points out that the most threatened reefs are found in
southeast Asia, where an estimated 82 percent are considered to be
at medium or high risk.
</P>
<P>
Now the Hainan provincial government is trying to persuade
fishermen to take up planting crops or marine focused projects
such as fish farming.
</P>
<P>
Already the new policy seems to be having an effect. After
hearing of the problem Xu Wenming from Dongge Town near Wenchang
city in south China's Hainan Province, has wound up his 15 year
old coral mining business and pulled down his lime-kiln.
</P>
<P>
"I now plan to plant peppers on the hills near my house and
raise some chickens," he said happily, his new future already
mapped out.
</P>
<P>
And in the last two months since the coral ban was imposed
more than 150 families who have traditionally worked the coral
reefs have stopped.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
