<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaria Affects 2 Million Ethiopians Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Minister of Health
Lamisso Hayeso said an estimated two million people in Ethiopia
are affected by malaria every year.
</P>
<P>
This year traditionally safer areas including Addis Ababa have
been hit by malaria epidemic as a result of changes in weather
conditions, the Ethiopian Herald Tuesday quoted Vice-Minister
Lamisso as telling local journalists.
</P>
<P>
Lamisso said the epidemic has shown a declining trend in the
past few days while preparations have been underway to undertake
massive spraying of anti-mosquito chemicals in the states hit
hardly by the epidemic and to import DDT and other chemicals.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that the Ministry of Health had issued an early
warning last year but could not produce the expected results due
to lack of adequate control systems.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that a consignment of anti-malaria medicines
donated by the World Health Organization (WHO) has already
arrived at Addis Ababa airport where it is due to be distributed
to all parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Vice-Minister urged the various government departments at
all levels, health institutions, and non-governmental
organizations to work concertedly in the fight against the
epidemic.
</P>
<P>
About 40 million of Ethiopia's 58 million people live in
malaria-prone localities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
