<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Govt Urged to Enforce Town Planning Act </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The National Construction
Council of Zambia has urged the government to enforce town
planning act, saying that only seven percent of Lusaka's
buildings have been constructed by registered contractors.
</P>
<P>
The Post newspaper Tuesday quoted council president Francis
Ndilila as saying that there is rampant disregard of the act
resulting in poorly constructed buildings in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
Ndilila has called for the strict enforcement of the act to
attain sound development of the cities in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said it is shocking to see that despite the act being in
place, law enforcers have left the increasing emergence of shanty
compounds unchecked.
</P>
<P>
It is clear, said Ndilila, that the law enforcers have been
benefiting from illegal buildings.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to immediately implement policies on
selected liberalization if the local industry is to survive.
</P>
<P>
"We have liberalized entirely to the point that people are now
coming and just playing here as our local industries cannot
compete with them," said Ndilila.
</P>
<P>
While this is the case in the region, he noted that the
government has been heavily taxing the local industries, making
their products uncompetitive.
</P>
<P>
"We are not saying that government should scrap tax because we
know the state needs the funds," he said, adding, "What we are
asking for are incentives that will make us competitive."
</P>
<P>
The official said high taxation has led to local contractors
being more expensive compared to other regional competitors while
they are equally as good as their foreign counterparts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
