<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Egyptian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Egyptian newspapers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Al Ahram:
</P>
<P>
-- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said Monday the
Palestinian-Israeli peace agreement must be implemented without
any conditions.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-brokered Wye River Accord, which was signed in
Washington in October, stipulates that Israel withdraws its troops
from another 13 percent of the West Bank in return for tougher
Palestinian actions against Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu ordered the
suspension of implementing the accord due to the pressure from the
hardliners in his coalition and the mounting violence in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Moussa dubbed as sheer procrastination Netanyahu's request to
shelve the execution of the deal because of domestic problems.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President is shuttling between Israel and the Palestinian
self-rule area to convince the two sides to stick to the terms of
the deal.
</P>
<P>
Al Akhbar:
</P>
<P>
-- Moussa said Monday Egypt and the Democratic Republic of
Congo have agreed upon three agreements during the visit of
Congolese President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
The agreements cover prevention of dual taxation, investment
protection and bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
The DRCongo has been plagued by fightings between forces loyal
to Kabila and the rebels. Egypt has helped broker a cease-fire
between the Congolese government and Uganda and Rwanda, the rebels'
backers.
</P>
<P>
Kabila wrapped up his three-day visit to Egypt Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Al Gomhuria:
</P>
<P>
-- Egyptian Minister of Information Safwat Al-Sherif said
Monday that Egypt will sign a contract before the end of this year
for the manufacture and launch of another Egyptian satellite.
</P>
<P>
The new satellite, which will be built by French Matra Marconi
company, is expected to be put into orbit in 1999. The satellite
will carry 12 space channels which will transmit 84 TV channels
under the digital system and its transmission will cover the
African continent, the Middle East and south Europe.
</P>
<P>
The first Egyptian satellite was launched on April 28.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Gazette:
</P>
<P>
-- The Israeli government Sunday night raised the issue of the
Israeli spy Azzam Azzam, currently serving a 15-year term in an
Egyptian jail, with Clinton during his visit to the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Following a dinner banquet hosted by Netanyahu for Clinton,
Netanyahu arranged a meeting between Clinton and the family of the
convicted Druze spy.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted Clinton as promising to do his best to
guarantee the release of the Israeli spy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
