<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan's Kravchenko Dedicates Gold to Wife, Son </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan's Vadim Kravchenko,
who successfully defended his 4-km individual pursuit title here
on Tuesday, wanted to dedicate his gold medal to his wife and son.
</P>
<P>
"I want to dedicate this medal to my wife and 5-year-old son,"
said Kravchenko, who defeated Japanese Noriyuki Iijima to the
second place in the final, timing 4:42.799 against Iijima's
4:45.215.
</P>
<P>
Kravchenko, who set the Asian record at the last Games in
Hiroshima, Japan, added: "I am very happy with the victory
although I had not got good time here."
</P>
<P>
He said the track here could be a discouraging factor for
improving the record.
</P>
<P>
The 39-year-old Army lieutenant said he aimed at winning the
Asian champion and a medal at the Olymic Games.
</P>
<P>
Iijima, who along with another Japanese is the first
professional Keirin racers competing here, won the silver.
</P>
<P>
In the race for the third place, Kyrgyzstan's Evgeniy Vakker
beat China's Shi Guijun to win the bronze. Vakker timed 4:47.347
against Shi's 4:53.475. 
</P>
