<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Pick Up Major Awards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Five Chinese scientists who
have made outstanding contributions in various fields picked up
prizes under the Wong Tan Ping Science and Technology award valued
at 100,000 yuan (about 12,000 U.S. dollars) each today.
</P>
<P>
Selected because of their success in the 1996 and 1997 National
Science and Technology Advancement Prize, the five are acclaimed
for their development work in onshore and offshore oil drilling
techniques, high performance computers, the design of advanced
locomotives and improvements in continuous steel rolling equipment.
</P>
<P>
The prizes were established by Wong Tan Ping, an elderly
overseas Chinese, in 1992, who provided five million U.S. dollars
for the award scheme which selects five winners each year.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the award ceremony Zhu Lilan, China's Minister of
Science and Technology, urged other scientists and technicians to
learn from the winners whose hard work and devotion to each of
their particular disciplines was an inspiration.
</P>
<P>
She expressed the wish that a wide range of awards could be
made available to encourage more young scientists as they are the
backbone of China's future development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
