<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiangsu to Close Small Thermal Power Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province
has decided to close small thermal power plants over the next
three years.
</P>
<P>
The provincial electricity bureau recently issued a directive
that all plants operating three generators with installed
capacities of less than 100,000 kw each should cease operations by
the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
Local sources note that the province's generating units with
installed capacities at that level account for a third of the
total.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities issued the directive in answer to the fact
that small thermal plants create serious pollution and waste large
amounts of coal.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has attempted to ease energy
shortages in recent years by constructing large efficient
generators and placing limitations on smaller units.
</P>
<P>
Small thermal power plants supplied 20 percent less power
during 1998 than in 1987.
</P>
<P>
The local official in charge of the power construction said the
rapid development of power construction in recent years has ended
the situation in which insufficient power supply hindered economic
development. Large generating units can easily fill the gap
resulting from the closure of smaller plants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World-Bank Financed Power Project Starting Generating Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The first 180,000-kw
generating unit at the Wanjiazhai Water Conservation Project on
the middle reaches of the Yellow River has recently begun
generating power.
</P>
<P>
The project, partially funded by the World Bank, was completed
33 days ahead of schedule, said an engineer in charge of its
construction.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the project began in 1994. It will eventually
be able to generate electricity and control flooding and menance
of ice runs, in addition to diverting water.
</P>
<P>
The facility will have six generating units with a combined
capacity of 1.08 million kw. In 1999, three more generating units
will be added.
</P>
<P>
On completion in 2000, the project will be able to provide 1.2
billion cu.m. of water for Shanxi Province, 200 million cu.m. for
Inner Mongolia, and 2.75 billion kwh of electricity to north
China, annually.
</P>
<P>
This project is also financed by Shanxi Province, the Inner
Mongolia Autonomous Region and the Chinese Ministry of Water
Resources, with total investments of 12 billion yuan (about 1.4
billion U.S. dollars), of which 400 million U.S. dollars will be
covered by loans from the World Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
