<HEADLINE> New Zealand Govt Announces Millennium Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government
has decided to provide over two million New Zealand dollars (1.05
million U.S. dollars) for the country's millennium celebrations in
Gisborne, Mt. Hikurangi and the Chatham Islands, the Evening Post
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The decision, announced Tuesday, represents the first round of
funding for communities and organizations that have applied for
financial assistance for projects to celebrate the year 2000, the
Wellington-based newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The Chatham Islands will be the first inhabited place to see
the dawn in 2000, Mt. Hikurangi on the East Coast the first place
on the mainland, and Gisborne the first city.
</P>
<P>
David Beatson, chairman of the Towards 2000 task force of New
Zealand, was quoted as saying that cabinet ministers have approved
the recommendations for funding allocations by the task force.
</P>
<P>
A further 575,000 New Zealand dollars (260,000 U.S. dollars)
would be allocated to national projects for celebrations, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The total budget for the millennium celebrations in New Zealand
will be 10 million New Zealand dollars (about 5.3 million U.S.
dollars), the NZ Television reported Tuesday. 
</P>
