<HEADLINE> China's Legislature Considers Budgetary Watchdog </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The setting up of a special
sub-committee charged with supervising China's national budget is
being considered by the National People's Congress Standing
Committee, the country's top legislature.
</P>
<P>
A bill proposing the establishment of the Budgetary Work
Committee of the NPC Standing Committee will be submitted to the
forthcoming legislative session which starts on December 23.
</P>
<P>
The plan was discussed by a meeting of deputies of the NPC
Standing Committee today, which was chaired by Li Peng, chairman
of the Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
They said that it would assist fiscal and monetary controls
allowing budgetary measures to play their full part in maintaining
and progressing China's national economic development.
</P>
<P>
During the planned seven-day legislative session, a draft
explanation on implementing the Nationality Law in the Macao
Special Administrative Region would be debated. It will also
review a revised draft of the Copyright Law.
</P>
<P>
Other draft laws related to securities, military service, the
punishment for financial crimes and the appeal process for
contract disputes will also be discussed.
</P>
<P>
The legislature will also consider two bills confirming the
legal status of the court and the prosecutor's office of the
Xinjiang Military Corps for Production and Construction.
</P>
<P>
Also on the agenda are two international conventions waiting to
be validated: the International Labor Organization Convention
Concerning Minimum Age for Admission to Employment and a consular
treaty with the Canadian government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
