<HEADLINE> Three-Way Summit Held Amid Doubts on Planned Israeli Redeployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. President Bill
Clinton at last brought Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
and Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat for a
three-way summit Tuesday morning at the Erez border Crossing
between Israel and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
The summit came less than one day after the Palestinians took
a decisive step on the peace process as hundreds of members of
the Palestine National Council (PNC) and other leadership bodies
convened and reaffirmed the annulment of anti-Israel provisions
in the Palestinian charter.
</P>
<P>
Israel, which linked the holding of a three-way summit with
the outcome of the PNC meeting, welcomed the PNC decision to
revoke the anti-Israel charter.
</P>
<P>
But Aviv Bushinsky, spokesman for Netanyahu, told Israel TV
before the start of the summit that he was still doubting about
whether the Palestinians will fulfill their other obligations
before Friday, the day when Israel is scheduled to carry out the
second of three withdrawals from the West Bank stipulated in a
recent peace deal.
</P>
<P>
While describing the PNC decision on revising the charter
as "an important step" on the Palestinian side, Netanyahu said
Monday it was only the first step and "other compliances" are
needed before Israel begins to implement the accords.
</P>
<P>
He put the pending troop withdrawal on hold last week amid
widespread clashes in the West Bank, which were sparked by
Israel's refusal to release Palestinian political prisoners, and
what he called Arafat's unilateral declaration of a Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
Bushinsky said Israel had not changed its positions on all
these issues.
</P>
<P>
Israel media reported Monday that the U.S. would propose a
compromise calling for a two-week time-out in the implementation
of the peace accords to enable the two sides to smooth over
their differences.
</P>
<P>
But Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said at a late
night briefing in Jerusalem that the U.S. is still hopeful the
redeployment will take place on schedule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
