<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: U.S. Executives Ignorant of Energy Cost Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. corporate executives
are unaware of the massive cost-saving possibilities of installing
energy-efficient electrical equipment, said a survey report Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the national survey of CFO (chief financial officer)
Magazine readers last August, most of the executives who responded
felt they had little control over electrical energy costs and more
than half stated they were not involved at all in their company's
energy decisions.
</P>
<P>
The survey was sponsored by the Energy Cost Savings Council
(ECSC), a coalition of manufacturers, utilities, industry groups
and government agencies working together to inform American
business leaders about the bottom line benefits of upgrading
buildings with new electrotechnologies.
</P>
<P>
According to ECSC, survey results revealed most financial
executives still considered energy costs a fixed expense, and knew
little about energy management as a means of cutting operating
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
Citing estimates made by the U.S. Department of Energy, ECSC
said that only about one-third of U.S. companies were using
state-of-the-art electrotechnologies, ranging from more
energy-efficient lighting and transformers to HVAC (heating,
ventilating and air conditioning) systems and completely automated
building systems which monitor and control energy consumption.
</P>
<P>
Financial executives usually believed that the capital
investment to upgrade their buildings was too high. But according
to ECSC, investments in energy-efficient electrical products
upgrades, which can reduce energy costs by up to 50 percent
annually, can be recouped in as little as two to three years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
