<HEADLINE> Sixteen Giant Salamanders Stolen from Chongqing Zoo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Sixteen of the seventeen
giant salamanders in southwest China's Chongqing Zoo were stolen
on December 10.
</P>
<P>
A zoo official said the stolen salamanders are above ten years
old on average, and the remaining one is female and over 40 years
old.
</P>
<P>
He said that giant salamanders, which are state-protected
amphibious animals, live in rivers and streams at an altitude of 200
to 1,000 meters in water about 20 C.
</P>
<P>
He said he's worried about the fate of the stolen animals
because of the winter weather in Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
Local police said the thieves may have first climbed over the
two- meter-high wall around the salamander hall and pierced open
the wooden gate with a sharp knife. The police have made public
two telephone numbers in hopes of getting information about the
case.
</P>
<P>
The Chongqing Zoo, located in the western suburbs, is home to
120 species of rare animals, including giant pandas and
golden-hair monkeys. Eight cases of the theft of rare birds and
animals have occurred since early this year, which, analysts say,
is related to the local people's taste for wild animals and the
fashion of keeping pets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
