<HEADLINE> Hughes Buying U.S. Satellite to Strengthen Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Hughes Electronics Corp.
announced Monday it will buy U.S. Satellite Broadcasting Co. for
1.3 billion U.S. dollars in cash and stock in a move to strengthen
its position as the largest U.S. satellite television service.
</P>
<P>
Both companies are pioneers in direct broadcast satellite
technology, which now has about eight million customers in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The purchase, expected to be completed between March and June
of next year, will add about 800 million to 900 million dollars to
Hughes's revenues in the first year and reduce annual costs by 160
million to 180 million dollars as the two companies consolidate
redundant operations, such as billing, customer service and
broadcasting centers, sources said.
</P>
<P>
The combined company will become a stronger competitor to cable
operators, analysts said. Hughes's DIRECTV plans to expand its
185-channel programming lineup to more than 210 channels through
the addition of the premium channels owned by U.S. Satellite
Broadcasting Co.
</P>
<P>
The deal had been widely expected following last month's move
by DIRECTV's rival EchoStar Communication Corp. to buy the
satellite television assets of News Corp Ltd. and MCI WorldCom
Inc., analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
