<HEADLINE> World Food Program Aid Projects Fruitful In Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The projects under the World
Food Program's Chapter 3779 in western Hubei Province have been
completed recently and have played a remarkable role in promoting local
agricultural production and improving the lives of farmers.
</P>
<P>
This is the largest free-aid project the WFP has provided to
China. It began in 1991 and is aimed at developing agriculture in
western Hubei, expanding local irrigation systems, planting trees,
building roads and training personnel.
</P>
<P>
The water conservation component, which constitutes most of the
program, has increased the planting area of rice by over 1,100
hectares, the irrigation area by nearly 20 percent, and rice
output by 90 percent per hectare.
</P>
<P>
As a result of this project, 3,100 hectares of trees were
planted, bringing the forest coverage in the region to 45.9
percent in 1997, from 36.7 percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 kilometers of rural highways and roads were also
completed, which has helped accelerate the development of the local
market economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
