<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Finds Seven White-fin Dolphins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Calculating from current results, China now only has less
than 100 white-fin dolphins," predicted Wang Yamin, an official
from the Fishery Department of the Ministry of Agriculture. China
found 23 white-fin dolphins in a similar activity last year.
</P>
<P>
The seven-day-long activity started from December 4, with
results of finding five dolphins in central China's Hubei
province, one in Hunan province and a young one in east China's
Jiangxi province.
</P>
<P>
Wang noted that the finding of the young dolphin is of great
importance to the protection of the species.
</P>
<P>
The white-fin dolphin is a unique animal living in China's
Yangtze River and has been put under the state primary protection.
</P>
<P>
In the past century, because of the development of the
Yangtze, the deteriorating of the water quality in the river and
the decreasing of fish species, the number of the dolphins
decreased by a large margin. The illegal fishing tools also
killed dolphins in a large quantity.
</P>
<P>
To protect dolphins, the country has set up two state-level
protection zones in Hubei province. However, Wang said he
worried about the fate of dolphins.
</P>
<P>
"The natural protection zone can provide only part of the
protection as the water quality of the Yangtze is still
deteriorating," Wang said, adding that scientists want to move
the dolphins out to a safe new home, but the out-of-date fishing
technique restricted the launching of such a plan.
</P>
<P>
Scientists also found some 1,500 black finless porpoises,
another animal under the state protection, during this
monitoring.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
