<HEADLINE> ASEAN Countries Begin Summit in Hanoi (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Leaders from the nine member
countries of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
began a two-day summit here Tuesday morning to find ways to boost
ASEAN cooperation and revive the region's battered economy.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting are Brunei Sultan Haji Hassanal Bolkiah,
Indonesian President B.J. Habibie, Lao Prime Minister Sisavath
Keobounphanh, Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, Myanmar
Prime Minister Shan Shwe, Philippine President Joseph Estrada,
Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong, Thai Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai and Vietnamese Prime Minister Phan Van Khai.
</P>
<P>
High on the agenda are measures for overcoming the economic
woes which some ASEAN members have been facing since last year
when a financial crisis struck the region.
</P>
<P>
The leaders, who are meeting under the theme of "unity and
cooperation for an ASEAN of peace, stability and equitable
development," are also expected to discuss how to strengthen
political and security cooperation and accelerate economic
integration between the member countries.
</P>
<P>
A number of documents including the Hanoi Declaration, the
Hanoi Plan of Action and a document on what ASEAN officials called
"bold measures" for putting an end to the financial crisis and
achieving economic recovery will be considered and approved by the
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Presiding over the opening ceremony, Vietnamese Prime Minister
Khai, who is also chairman of the summit, said the leaders will
"exchange views on and look for measures to bring back the
region's sustained development" and the decisions of the summit
"will constitute a clear message on the part of regional countries
and peoples to the world about ASEAN's determination to jointly
address challenges and difficulties for further development."
</P>
</TEXT>
