<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Economy Survives Asian Crisis: RBA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Australia's economy survived
the Asian economic crisis in 1998 but was set for slower economic
growth, Australia's central bank governor said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ian Macfarlane, governor of the Reserve Bank of Australia,
boosted his predictions for economic growth in 1998 to four
percent, from three percent he forecast earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
The economic outcomes for the past year had been pretty good,
the governor said in a speech to an Australian parliamentary
committee Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
"Australia's economic performance has exceeded our
expectations, and to my knowledge the expectations of virtually
all forecasters".
</P>
<P>
But he warned of a slowdown next year due to the weaker outlook
for the world economy.
</P>
<P>
The governor said the country's economic growth was likely to
come in at 2.5 to 3.0 percent in the 1998-1999 financial year
ending June 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
He predicted inflation was likely to come in at two percent at
the end of the year while the current account deficit looked set
to average five percent of gross domestic product in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Asian crisis had hit at a time when the Australian economy
was in good shape, with strong growth and low inflation in
mid-1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
