<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Shrimp Exporters May Suffer Huge Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Frozen shrimp exporters of
Bangladesh may suffer a loss as high as 1.28 billion taka (26.4
million U.S. dollars) this year, President of Bangladesh Frozen
Shrimp Exporters Association (BFSEA) Golam Mostafa said.
</P>
<P>
The huge loss was mainly a result of declining prices in the
buyers' market by 30 to 40 percent, Mostafa said in southeastern
Chittagong Monday, press reports here said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He demanded financial assistance from the government to
modernize the processing plants to meet the needs of quality
frozen shrimps from the buyers, particularly those from the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
Shrimp exporters in the country had been passing through
hardships in the past two years, and the situation began to
aggravate in July this year with a sharp fall in price in the
international market, Mostafa said.
</P>
<P>
Shrimps worth 3.77 billion taka (77.7 million dollars) now
piled up in Bangladesh, according to the BFSEA president, because
of the fierce competition from other shrimp exporting countries
and the inability of the country's small producers to maximize
output at lower cost.
</P>
<P>
Some 77 shrimp processing factories out of the 123 had already
closed down due to the shortage of working capital in the last
couple of years, and plant owners refused to take fresh loans as
they could not repay the existing loans of 1.50 billion taka (30.9
million dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh usually exports shrimps worth 2 to 3 billion taka
(41.67-62.5 million U.S. dollars) during the peak season from
September to October, but this year only 500 to 600 million taka's
(10.41 to 12.50 million dollars) worth of shrimps were exported,
experts said.
</P>
<P>
The country's shrimp production this year might fall by as much
as 40 percent to around 15,000 tons from last year's 25,000 tons,
reports said.
</P>
<P>
There are about 1.5 million professional fishermen in
Bangladesh, and the export of frozen food, both fish and shrimp,
contributes about 8.7 percent to the country's total foreign
exchange earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Sugarcane Farmers Demonstrate for Higher Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of Thai sugarcane
farmers from the northeast demonstrated outside the Government
House here Tuesday to press demand for higher prices.
</P>
<P>
Police cordoned the streets leading to the House, but there was
no report of clashes between the demonstrators and police.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Bhichai Rattakul, taking charge of
government affairs during the absence of Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai who is in Hanoi attending an ASEAN summit, canceled a
scheduled interview with Xinhua reporters because of the
demonstration.
</P>
<P>
One of his secretaries said Bhichai had to cancel the
interview, originally scheduled for mid-Tuesday, because he was
fully occupied and because the streets leading to the Government
House were cordoned.
</P>
<P>
The sugarcane farmers demanded a guaranteed price of 630 baht
(17.5 U.S. dollars) per ton. Monday the farmers gathered in front
of Industry Minister Suwat Liptapallop's house, parking 120 trucks
and pickups in front of it, causing traffic jam in the area.
</P>
<P>
The farmers accused the government of "ignoring the plight of
cane planters" by making a decision to fix the cane price at 470
baht (13 dollars) per ton.
</P>
<P>
They threatened to lean "an army of thousands" of planters on
trucks laden with cane crops to Bangkok if the government failed
to meet their demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
