<HEADLINE> Boeing, Delta Sign Contracts With Chinese Airlines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Boeing has signed a
contract with China Eastern Airlines to help convert two passenger
MD-11 jetliners of the Chinese carrier into freighters.
</P>
<P>
The conversion work, Boeing said Monday, includes the removal
of passenger furnishings and the installation of a 140-inch-wide
side cargo door and a main deck cargo-handling system.
</P>
<P>
However, the Seattle-based largest aircraft builder of the
world did not disclose the value of the contract.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, Delta Air Lines, said it had signed a
comprehensive agreement with China Southern Airlines providing
code-sharing on flights between China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Recognizing China as "one of the great growth markets in the
world," Delta said the new service will "allow Delta to fill a
critical marketplace deficiency by creating important new service
options for business and leisure travelers from the U.S. to China."
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Delta will purchase seats on China
Southern's three-times-per-week Boeing 777-200 service between Los
Angeles on the U.S. West Coast and Guangzhou, of southern China.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Chinese airline will purchase seats on Delta
flights from Los Angeles to certain other U.S. destinations.
</P>
</TEXT>
