<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia Hit by Storms, Cold Snap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Two strong storms combining
cold winds and heavy rains hit Cambodia in the past few days,
causing serious damage to houses and villagers.
</P>
<P>
The first storm, called Fair, struck Sihanoukville Friday and
Saturday, while the second storm, dubbed Faith, assaulted the same
coastal area early Sunday. The high winds and heavy rains brought
by the storms destroyed 25 houses and seriously injured one
villager, the Cambodia Daily Tuesday quoted the provincial police
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Following the storms, temperature plunged to 16.4 degrees
Celsius in the highlands, the lowest temperature in Cambodia since
1993. In Phnom Penh, temperature dropped to 18.7 degrees Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists attributed the unusual cold snap to two typhoons
that swept through Southeast Asia and to the worldwide abnormal
weather phenomenon known as El Nino.
</P>
<P>
The storms were expected to fade Tuesday morning, but
cooler-than-normal weather will continue into next year, said an
official of the meteorology department.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of families living on riverbanks, by roadside and
near railroads have been subjected to cold winds and rain
battering their flimsy shacks. Many people had to cover themselves
with a mosquito net because they had not enough blankets and
clothes.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the cold weather is harming agriculture, too. By
this time of the year, normally 80 percent of rice crops should be
harvested. But this year, only 20 to 30 percent have been
harvested. And many crops were damaged by strong winds and heavy
rains. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
