<HEADLINE> Myanmar Holds Intercountry Meeting on Childhood Illness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 15 (Xinhua) -- An intercountry meeting on
integrated management of childhood illness (IMCI) is being held
here to discuss the implementation of tactics of the IMCI of
United Nations agencies.
</P>
<P>
The four-day discussions, which began Monday, cover the
implementation of the IMCI of the World Health Organization (WHO)
and the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) in 1996 and
maternal health care service.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar Deputy Health Minister Dr. Mya Oo pointed out that the
rate of outbreak of pneumonia, diarrhea, measles and malaria
diseases drops in Myanmar due to vaccines.
</P>
<P>
The diseases are reportedly causing death of children under
five especially in the developing countries due to malnutrition in
them.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting are altogether 33 delegates from eight
Southeast Asian nations and 11 observers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Myanmar has launched the National Immunization Days
(NIDs) for three years since 1995 with 5.33 million or 96
percent, 5.5 million or 99 percent and 5.503 million or 97
percent children under five receiving polio immunization
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The number of reported poliomyelitis cases in 1988 was 60 but
there was only nine cases in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In cooperation with the WHO, the UNICEF, the UNDP (United
Nations Development Program), the Japanese and Australian
governments as well as non-governmental organizations, the first
day of this year's Myanmar NIDs activities was launched last
Saturday, targeting 5.8 million children under five to be given
oral polio vaccines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
