<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senile Dementia Threatens Beijing's Senior Citizens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The incidence of senile
dementia has been on the rise in the Chinese capital in recent
years, according to a survey reported in today's Beijing Morning
Post.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by Xuanwu Hospital, reveals that some 20
percent of the elderly people questioned are suffering from the
disease, a common disorder which can threaten the life of the aged.
</P>
<P>
Senior citizens, considered to be those above the age of 60,
now account for 12.7 percent of Beijing's population, or 1.2
million people, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The survey says that the incidence of senile dementia among
females is nearly twice that among males, and the incidence is
even higher among the poorly educated.
</P>
<P>
Xuanwu and Anding hospitals are the only two in Beijing
specializing in the treatment of this malady.
</P>
<P>
A doctor from Xuanwu Hospital said that in China, dementia is
mostly caused by cerebrovascular diseases, and many people are
able to recover through early therapy.
</P>
<P>
The doctor also cautioned people to pay attention to the
changes brought about by aging, such as as memory loss,
disorientation and confusion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Protects Environment While Building Railways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The construction of the Xi'an to
Ankang railway line in northwest China has not affected the
historic sites in the city of Xi'an or the scenery in the Qinling
Range, but rather has added to their beauty.
</P>
<P>
Not far from the mausoleum of Qin Shihuang, the first emperor
of China, a 4,000-meter-long rainbow bridge spans a large stretch
of farmland.
</P>
<P>
One construction company manager said the building of the
bridge is intended to protect the original landscape and farmland.
</P>
<P>
Li Henian, chief designer of the railway, said that 364 million
yuan was budgeted for the protection of environment along the
railway, of which 90 million has been used for debris removal, 18
million for polluted water and emission treatment, and 1.5 million
for planting trees and grass.
</P>
<P>
But in actual operation, he said, many construction companies
exceeded their budgets in order to pass inspection by local
environmental protection authorities.
</P>
<P>
The debris from the Qinling tunnel, the longest railway tunnel
being built in China, must be hauled some 15 kilometers away and
dumped into a specially designed site, which eventually will be
turned into farmland.
</P>
<P>
The polluted water from the tunnel construction site first
flows into a treatment pool before it is released into the valley,
and, Li said, more than one million yuan has been spent on the
treatment of polluted water from the tunnel alone.
</P>
<P>
To avoid the scenic spots in Zhashui County in the middle of
the Qinling Range, the railway is designed to extend in a
round-about way, which added to the cost of the railway, but left
the scenic surroundings untouched.
</P>
<P>
The 268-kilometer-long Xi'an-Ankang railway, linking the
Lanzhou-Lianyungang railway in the north and the
Xiangfan-Chongqing railway in the south, is scheduled to be
completed on October 1, 2000, when it will form another
north-south trunk railway line.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0316 </DOCNO>
