<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Deficit Drops in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Trade deficit in the
Philippines dropped by 91.2 percent to 837 million U.S. dollars in
the first 10 months of this year from 9.507 billion dollars a year
ago, due to a massive reduction in imports, the National
Statistics Office said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a monthly report released here, the office said that
merchandise exports were valued at 24.387 billion dollars in the
first 10 months of the year, a 17.9-percent increase from 20.689
billion dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the office said, imports amounted to 25.225
billion dollars in the period, which was 16.5 percent lower than
the 30.196 billion dollars recorded a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The office also said that two-way trade transactions for that
period fell by 2.5 percent to 49.612 billion dollars from 50.885
billion dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
In October alone, the total trade suffered a 13.6-percent
shortfall to 4.960 billion dollars from 5.740 billion dollars last
year, the office said.
</P>
<P>
The trade balance for the month was a surplus of 125 million
dollars, it said.
</P>
<P>
This is the fifth consecutive month when a surplus was posted
in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
