<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronicle of Major Events In China Since 1978 (3-1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The following is the third
part of the chronicle of major events which have taken place in
China since the Third Plenum of the 11th Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC), as compiled by the CPC Central
Commitee Literature Research Center:
</P>
<P>
1993:
</P>
<P>
-- The First Session of the Eighth National People's
Congress, held between March 15-31, approved a motion to amend the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
The constitutional amendment affirmed that China was in the
primary stage of socialism, and its basic task was to carry out the
socialist modernization in accordance with the theory of
building socialism with Chinese characteristics; that the
rural household contract responsibility system which links income
with output was the mode of the socialist collective economy; and
that the country would build a socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
At the session, Jiang Zemin was elected Chinese president and
chairman of the Central Military Commission of the People's
Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
-- Wang Daohan, president of the Association for Relations
Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS), and Koo Chen-fu, chairman of
the Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF) of Taiwan, held talks in
Singapore between April 27-29. The two sides signed four documents.
</P>
<P>
This was the first meeting between leaders of authorized
cross-Straits nongovernmental institutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronicle of Major Events In China Since 1978 (3-2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin attended the first informal
leadership conference of the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation
(APEC) in Seattle on November 20 and gave a speech calling
for greeting the 21st century with a peaceful and prosperous
world.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between Chinese President Jiang Zemin and
U.S. President Bill Clinton on the day before the conference
represented the first high-level exchange between top leaders of
the two nations since February 1989.
</P>
<P>
-- The State Council issued a December 15 announcement
outlining its decision to implement a new taxation system which
separated central and local taxes.
</P>
<P>
-- The State Council announced a decision on December 25 to
reform the financial system and adopt macro-adjustment mechanism
making the People's Bank of China the central bank responsible for
independently carrying out the nation's monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
-- A meeting to commemorate the 100th birth anniversary of Mao
Zedong was held on December 26.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin gave a speech pointing to Mao Zedong
Thought as an everlasting theoretical treasure of Party members,
as well as a spiritual pillar of the Chinese nation and the
guiding precept for socialist modernization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronicle of Major Events In China Since 1978 (3-3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
1995:
</P>
<P>
-- The Taiwan Work Office under the CPC Central Committee and
the Taiwan Affairs Office of the State Council hosted a reception
on January 30 to mark China's Lunar New Year.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang presented a speech focusing on the need for
continuous efforts to promote reunification of the motherland. He
also introduced an eight-point proposal for developing
cross-Straits relations and promoting peaceful reunification.
</P>
<P>
-- The CPC Central Committee approved the resignation of
Beijing Mayor Chen Xitong in April.
</P>
<P>
Chen was then removed from his posts as a member
of the CPC Central Committee Political Bureau and a member of the
Central Committee in accordance with a decision made during the
Fifth Plenum of the 14th CPC Central Committee in September.
</P>
<P>
The plenum also recommended Chen's removal as a deputy to the
NPC in accordance with relevant legal procedures.
</P>
<P>
Chen was expelled from the Party on August 29, 1997, in
accordance with a decision by the CPC Central Commission for
Discipline Inspection.
</P>
<P>
The procuratorate department conducted extensive investigations
of the intricate cases involving Chen in accordance with law. The
Beijing Municipal Higher People's Court issued on July 31, 1998, a
verdict sentencing Chen to 16 years in prison for embezzlement and
dereliction of duty.
</P>
<P>
-- The CPC Central Committee and the State Council announced a
May 6 decision to accelerate scientific and technological progress
and adopt a strategy to use science and education to invigorate
the nation.
</P>
<P>
A national conference on science and technology was convened on
May 26.
</P>
<P>
-- The State Council approved Gyaincain Norbu as the 11th
Panchen Lama on November 29. The 11th Panchen was identified as
the reincarnated soul boy of the 10th Panchen Lama during a
ceremony held to draw lots from a golden urn.
</P>
</TEXT>
