<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Loan to South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) decided Monday to disburse 1.022 billion U.S. dollars
to South Korea under a 21 billion dollars loan approved last year.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the decision, IMF Deputy Managing Director Alassane
Ouattara said in a statement that South Korea "continues to make
commendable progress in its efforts to achieve economic recovery."
</P>
<P>
"The severe downturn in output has begun to moderate and there
are encouraging signs that the Korean economy will return to
positive growth during the course of next year," Ouattara said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the confidence of both consumers and
investors remained weak as "there was little room for complacency."
</P>
<P>
And the speed of the recovery would "depend to a great degree
on progress in corporate and financial restructuring," he said.
</P>
<P>
The 21 billion dollars loan approved on December 4 last year is
the largest single loan in the IMF's history, and the decision
Monday brings IMF's disbursement to a total of 19 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The next credit tranche is due in three months later. The IMF
loan is part of a 58 billion dollars international rescue package
including loans from the World Bank and the Asian Development
Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, U.S. Airline Sign Reciprocal Service Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 15 (Xinhua) -- China Southern Airlines
(CSA) and Delta Airlines of the Unites States will soon initiate a
reciprocal service agreement to increase efficiency.
</P>
<P>
CSA, with headquarters in Guangzhou, capital of Guangdong
Province, is the third Chinese airline sharing flight exchanges
with a foreign air company, following Air China and China Eastern
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed here Monday, Delta Airlines will
purchase seats on CSA's three weekly flights from Los Angeles to
Guangzhou, all of which use Boeing 777-200 planes.
</P>
<P>
CSA will purchase seats on Delta's flights from Los Angeles to
15 other American cities and will also join Delta's "Sky Miles"
frequent flyer program.
</P>
<P>
CSA now has a fleet of 90 aircraft and operates flights from
ten Chinese airports to more than 90 cities, accounting for 27
percent of the total air transportation volume within China.
</P>
<P>
Delta offers 5,132 flights to 354 cities in 61 countries around
the globe daily. Last year, Delta transported more than 100
million passengers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
