<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Impeachment Probe has Little Effect on Clinton Ratings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The impeachment debate last
week in Washington D.C. did little to change public opinions of
President Bill Clinton in the rest of the United States, according
to a new poll.
</P>
<P>
The poll conducted by the Pew Research Center for the People
and the Press found that two-thirds of American adults thought
President Clinton should not be impeached and removed from office.
</P>
<P>
Although more than half of those polled said they were unhappy
with the way the president had handled the congressional
investigation into his affair with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky, 61 percent still approved of the job he is doing
as president.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of respondents disapproved of the way
Republicans in Congress have handled the impeachment issue.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll, also released Monday,
indicated that about six in 10 Americans opposed impeachment
</P>
<P>
Seventy-one percent said Republicans are pursuing impeachment
for political reasons, compared with 61 percent who said Democrats
are acting out of political motivation.
</P>
<P>
Only one in three Americans closely followed last week's
impeachment debate and the votes by the House Judiciary
Committee. Nearly two-thirds said the media was paying too much
attention to the issue.
</P>
<P>
The Pew poll was based on telephone interviews with 1,201
adults who were interviewed from December 9- to 3. The margin of
error is plus or minus 3.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
The CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll was based on interviews with 865
adults on December 12 and 13. The margin of error is plus or
minus four percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0331 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: an American Doctor with a Mission in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, December 15 (Xinhua) -- A golden rule is always
followed in Sir Run Run Shaw Hospital in Hangzhou: emergency
patients will always be given top priority no matter their
financial situation.
</P>
<P>
The hospital has maintained this rule even though its budgets
have been hit because of unpaid fees and this has not shaken the
determination of Gordon Hadley, president of the American section
of the hospital, ex-vice president of Loma Linda University in
California and a former employee with WHO.
</P>
<P>
Most of the hospital's windows are tightly shut to enhance the
air conditioning system. "And there are quite a lot of patients
with terminal diseases here, so closing windows can also prevent
some desperate patients from jumping out to commit suicide. We
must be responsible for their safety as well as their health,"
said Mr Hadley.
</P>
<P>
"Mr Hadley is so considerate even with the minute details."
This is the kind of remark often be heard in this internationally
sponsored hospital. He even once found a sheet covered in oil
stains and cleaned it in his own washing machine, so the story
goes, according to a clerk in the hospital laundry.
</P>
<P>
Doctors and nurses can never predict when this 77-year-old
veteran doctor will appear on an unscheduled inspection. A
favorite time is during night shifts when he will also try to
solve any problems on the spot.
</P>
<P>
"This American gentleman not only brings us his medical skill,
but more importantly, his personal philosophy which dictates that
life should be cherished in any format," commented Professor Wu
Jinming, president of the Chinese section of the hospital and Mr
Hadley's long time partner.
</P>
<P>
Mr Hadley's daughter and son-in-law are also his colleagues
here, their expertise is in gynecology and emergency care.
</P>
<P>
The greatest sense of accomplishments for Mr Hadley comes, he
insists, from how others value his contribution and dearly
cherishes the West Lake Friendship Prize awarded to foreign
experts like him by the Zhejiang provincial government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
