<HEADLINE> U.S. Shuttle Astronauts Release Two Satellites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Home-coming astronauts
aboard space shuttle Endeavour released two satellites into space
Monday from the orbiting spacecraft's open cargo bay.
</P>
<P>
One of the two satellites was the result of a joint project of
the U.S. National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) and
the Argentine National Commission on Space Activities.
</P>
<P>
Designed to track whales, it would help test techniques to be
used in the future to follow endangered whale populations.
</P>
<P>
Another satellite, MightySat-1, was made of composite materials
rather than the customary aluminum alloys, so that scientists
could test the viability of composites in space.
</P>
<P>
Other experiments were also aboard the Department of Defense
satellite, including an advanced solar cell using heat rather than
light from the sun to make electricity.
</P>
<P>
Endeavour and its crew members are scheduled to land at Kennedy
Space Center, Florida, on Tuesday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
