<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Legislative Body to Meet Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian legislators have
decided that the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR), the
country's highest legislative body, should meet once every year,
the Indonesian Observer reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 1,000-member MPR currently assembles once every five years
to select a president and a vice president. It also issues state
guidelines and decrees, in addition to evaluating the president's
accountability speech.
</P>
<P>
All four factions of the House of Representatives agreed Monday
that the MPR must convene more than once every five years, in line
with the people's growing political awareness.
</P>
<P>
Budi Harsono, a legislator from the Armed Forces (ABRI)
faction, who presided over the meeting Monday, said the
recommendation to change the frequency of the MPR meetings will be
submitted to the leaders of the House in January.
</P>
<P>
"The proposal is aimed at empowering the MPR," Harsono said.
</P>
<P>
He said it would make a lot more sense if the president had to
present an annual accountability speech, rather than give one
every five years.
</P>
<P>
"And we, the legislators, would correct any mistakes made by
the president. We would try to correct the president before he
deviates too far," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
