<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0341 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Agro-Chemical Giants to Help China's Grain Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Fifteen major international
agro-chemical companies have formed an alliance to pool their
expertise to assist China's efforts to produce a better and safer
food supply, according to the China Pesticide Association (CPA).
</P>
<P>
The Crop Protection Association of China (CPAC), which was
recently set up in Beijing, will work with Chinese organizations
such as the State Bureau of Petroleum and Chemical Industries, the
Ministry of Agriculture and the CPA to introduce advanced crop
protection technologies to China.
</P>
<P>
The members of CPAC are AgroEvo, American Cyanamid, BASF,
Bayer, Dow, DuPont, Elf Atochem, FMC, Monsanto, Novartis,
Rhone-Poulenc, Rhom and Haas, Sumitomo, Uniroyal, and Zeneca,
which all have investments in China.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, CPA President Wang Luxian
said: "Scientific, safe and effective use of pesticides and other
crop protection methods should play a key role in the sustained
growth of China's agricultural sector."
</P>
<P>
China is the world's second largest producer of pesticides, but
still lags a long way behind the developed countries in product
structure, use of technology, the scale of operations, and basic
knowledge of crop protection, especially among those at the
working end, Wang commented.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that 30 percent of China's grain
growth in 1997 was attributed to the introduction of new
technology; compared to 60 percent among nations using advanced
agricultural techniques.
</P>
<P>
Guilford Ide, CPAC president and China Agro Business Manager of
DuPont Agricultural Chemicals Ltd., based in Shanghai, said, "With
22 percent of the world's population and seven percent of the
world's arable land, China has the greatest responsibility of any
nation to ensure an abundant and safe supply of food for its
population."
</P>
<P>
The CPAC is a member of the Asia-Pacific Crop Protection
Association, a subsidiary of the Global Crop Protection
Federation.
</P>
<P>
According to Ide, CPAC will focus on sponsoring initiatives and
activities to promote the responsible use of crop protection
technology; facilitating development and research in this area;
protecting related intellectual property rights; and providing
examples of environmental stewardship.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the application of state-of-the-art crop protection
mechanisms in agricultural production will help to consolidate and
improve the status of Chinese products on the world market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
