<HEADLINE> Norway Funds Sri Lanka's Leather Complex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The government of Norway has
provided a grant of 940,000 U.S. dollars to Sri Lanka for a
leather complex in the south of the country, the official Daily
News reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The project at Bata-Atha in Hambantota district will expand the
leather industrial sector without causing any damage to the
environment, create employment and alleviate poverty, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The leather production sector in Sri Lanka has not been
developed in keeping with the pace of that in other Asian
countries. The report said it was mainly because of the
restrictions placed on the industry for environmental
considerations.
</P>
<P>
Most leather tanneries in Sri Lanka are confined to small units
in Colombo suburbs.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly the new project will seek to relocate the tanneries
in one industrial estate with a hi-tech effluent treatment plant
to minimize adverse effects on the environment, said the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
