<HEADLINE> China's State-Owned Enterprises Reduce Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- China's on-going reform of
medium-sized and large state-owned enterprises has witnessed
remarkable progress this year, according to Zheng Silin,
vice-minister of the state economic and trade commission.
</P>
<P>
Zheng said Monday that the government has promoted a group of
capable personnel to be leaders of these enterprises, with a
number of unqualified managers removed from office.
</P>
<P>
"Of the 100 major pilot enterprises enjoying reform, 84 have
dispersed investment to different investors and 39 have been
listed," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zheng added that a number of successful companies including
Changhong, Legend and Haier, have become stronger, enabling them
to compete fairly with overseas companies. "Many medium-sized and
small companies have also reaped more profits." he said.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that the reforms in the textile, coal and oil
industries have also scored notable achievements. The oil
industry, for example, reported a profit of 615 million yuan in
October.
</P>
<P>
Zheng said that the government has also enhanced its efforts
for making arrangements for laid-off workers and for improving the
management of many enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government has decided to help the bulk of
state-owned enterprises become much more financially viable in the
next three years," he added.
</P>
<P>
"However, next year is a key period, and the government will
try to score substantial achievements in sorting out the financial
mess of many state-owned organisations," Zheng said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the focus will be placed on major industries.
"For example, we plan to reduce losses in the textile sector by
three billion yuan next year."  
</P>
</TEXT>
