<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Ministers at Odds on Civilian Militia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Justice Minister
Muladi said the government cannot commence its program to form
civilian militia units until a law endorsing the plan is enacted
by legislators.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after attending a hearing of House of Representatives
Commission I for security and defense Monday, Muladi said he will
advise President B.J. Habibie and Armed Forces (ABRI) Commander
General Wiranto to prepare a bill on the civilian militia.
</P>
<P>
"I insist that the program must not be implemented, because
there is no law for it. But if the government thinks the program
is really urgent, well, I think there must at least be a
government regulation," national newspapers Tuesday quoted Muladi
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the plan to form a civilian militia must be
outlined in a law, because it relates to the rights and
obligations of every citizen.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Article 20 of the 1982 Law on National
Defense stipulates that the establishment of trained civilians for
security purposes should be regulated by law.
</P>
<P>
Wiranto said Sunday that the government plans to arm thousands
of civilians with batons and shields to help security for next
year's general election, and to cope with the recent spate of
lawlessness in the crisis-ridden country.
</P>
<P>
He said the first phase of the recruitment process is to take
place in January 1999, and will be under the command of the
National Police.
</P>
<P>
Wiranto is already facing strong public criticism over the
mobilization last month of 125,000 untrained civilians to help
security for the special session of the People's Consultative
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Human rights activists, legislators and analysts criticized the
deployment of these civilian guards as they regularly ended up
brawling with residents and student protesters.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, Indonesia has been rocked by violent unrest,
including clashes between troops and students, and religious and
economic riots that have damaged scores of places of worship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0356 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Slams US For Drugs Blacklist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, December 14 (Xinhua) -- A senior Panamanian
congressman blasted the United States on Monday for including his
country in a blacklist of nations that were failing to fight the
drugs trade.
</P>
<P>
The United States was motivated to include Panama on its list
because of the failure of bilateral talks to set up a multilateral
anti-drugs center in Panama, Alberto Aleman Boyd, head of the
Panamanian Congress Anti-Drug Committee, said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. decision announced this weekend was
"arbitrary" and contrary to evidence that Panama had implemented
an anti-drugs policy.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Panamanian authorities seized 14.2 tons of marijuana,
and this year had confiscated about two tons of cocaine sent by
Colombian cartels to the U.S. and European markets, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the past four years, Panama's narcotics police seized over
74 tons of drugs, mostly cocaine and marijuana, sending nearly 400
traffickers to jail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
