<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Not to Probe Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Sydney 2000 bidding committee
will not be included in IOC's ongoing investigation which will
focus on the 2002 Salt Lake City Winter Games, International
Olympics Committee president Juan Antonio Samaranch confirmed in
Lausanne, Switzerland on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The words meant Sydney 2000 officials have distanced
themselves from allegations of bribery and corruption.
</P>
<P>
IOC's inquiry derived from its senior official Marc Hodler's
claims that cities bidding to stage the Olympic Games have paid
for votes.
</P>
<P>
Australian IOC executive board member Kevan Gosper said: "I
was on the bidding committee and we were never involved in any
bribery or corruption. No one ever approached me and I don't know
any of my colleagues who were either."
</P>
<P>
Gosper countered reports in the Sydney Morning Herald that
Sydney secured some African votes for cash.
</P>
<P>
As for Salt Lake City, Samaranch said on Monday IOC was
investigating the city because it had proof.
</P>
<P>
Salt Lake City chiefs have admitted that the Games officials
once presented tuition assistance and athlete training programs
to six direct relatives of IOC members during the bidding
process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
