<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin Votes in Local Legislative Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
visited a downtown polling place in Beijing this morning to cast
his vote in a local legislative election.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, general secretary of the Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China, cast his vote at Zhongnanhai, the
central government compound, at 09:00 this morning.
</P>
<P>
The Zhongnanhai ballot included candidates for the new People's
Congress in the Xicheng District, a major urban district in the
Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Other Party and government leaders, including Li Peng
and Premier Zhu Rongji, also cast their votes in other polling
places, including the Great Hall of the People.
</P>
<P>
Beijing held direct elections for deputies to people's
congresses in 10 urban districts, including
Xicheng, Dongcheng, Xuanwu and Chongwen. Some 5.67 million
Beijingers are expected to vote in today's elections.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Constitution grants the highest legislative power
to the National People's Congress, with local people's congresses
exercising related powers in localities.
</P>
<P>
The Constitution stipulates direct elections for deputies to
all people's congresses under the municipal level, including those
at the county, district and township levels.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese capital has 18 districts and counties, with
relevant laws and regulations stipulating that 4,403 deputies
should be elected before the end of 1998. Newly elected deputies
will serve five-year terms in accordance with the law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
