<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's New Yun-7 Aircraft Ready for Take Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Chang'an Airlines based in
northwestern tourist city of Xi'an will become the first to
introduce the new Yun-7-200A passenger aircraft, after signing a
contract with the Xi'an Aircraft Manufacturing Corp.
</P>
<P>
The Yun-7 series are the first China-made passenger aircraft
and constitute the largest fleet in China. Since first introduced
in 1984, they have had a clean safety record of 600,000 hours.
</P>
<P>
It has taken 10 years to develop the new Yun-7-200A model,
which has a Canadian engine and US-manufactured propeller and
navigation facilities as well as a range of new China-made
innovations, according to the manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
The 52-60 seater is 24.7 meters long, 29.2 meters wide, with
a maximum cruising speed of 456 kilometers per hour.
</P>
<P>
While it meets the international standards for safety, quality,
economic efficiency, comfort and maintenance, the Yun-7-200A only
costs about two thirds of a similar foreign aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The Chang'an Airlines, which operates about 30 domestic routes,
is one of the major users of the Yun-7 series. It has ordered two
Yun-7-200A aircraft and they will come into service early next
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
