<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0372 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> by Zhang Chaoxiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 15 (Xinhua) -- The price revolution has
been playing a decisive role in China's transformation of its
formerly rigid central economic planning into a market-oriented
economy.
</P>
<P>
A mere 20 years ago, the price of almost any commodity in
China was not determined by market demand but by the government.
</P>
<P>
This policy was originally introduced in order to cope with the
shortage in supply, but in reality it aggravated such shortages
since it had a negative effect on the enthusiasm of the workers.
</P>
<P>
The government set the prices for 91.3 percent of the country's
farm produce in 1979, 97.2 percent of the commodities handled by
the retail sector in 1978, and 100 percent of important raw
materials before 1978.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the supply of major daily necessities, ranging from
grain, cloth and meat to matches, were rationed. Consumers even in
big cities had to queue for what products were available.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong Province, authorized by the central government to
introduce special and flexible policies 20 years ago, was the
first region in the country to challenge this rigid pricing system.
</P>
<P>
In 1979, this coastal province in south China raised the price
of grain, which had been undervalued for a long time, along with
other agricultural products. This paved the way for the gradual
price liberalization of all agricultural products, and eventually
those in the industrial sector followed suit.
</P>
<P>
These 'revolutionary' reforms proved to be a success, and saw
the average farmer's per capita income in the province increase
to 644.71 yuan (about 77.67 US dollars based on the present
exchange rate) in 1987, from the relatively meager figure of
193.25 yuan in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Following Guandong's success in restructuring prices, a trial
project adjusting the cost of all agricultural products was
introduced in 1985 throughout the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0373 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reform Review: Price Reform Triggers a Revolution (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1992, the state monopoly for the buying and selling of grain
was ended, as was grain rationing. It wasn't long before the price
setting of consumer products generally was freed up throughout
China.
</P>
<P>
However, in the more strictly controlled manufacturing sector,
Guandong introduced a twin-track reform policy. This allowed
enterprises to set the price for part of their products depending
upon production quotas.
</P>
<P>
It had good reasons for this cautious approach as unfettered
price reforms can easily trigger off price hikes. In 1980, the
retail price index rose by 8.5 percent in Guangdong compared with
the eight percent rise recorded in the preceding 28 years.
</P>
<P>
However, provincial officials moved forward with enthusiasm and
sought ways to introduce a series of new regulatory measures. They
set up reserves for major new commodities and established a "price
risk fund" which helped overcome several waves of rather large
price hikes.
</P>
<P>
Increased production brought about by the reforms also helped
offset the aftermath of price hikes. While the living expenditure
price index of workers rose by 80.64 percent in Guangdong in 1987,
the gross agricultural and industrial output value increased by
over 300 percent and workers' wages by over 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
With an ample market supply, prices eventually became stablized
and between 1978 and 1997, the retail price ratio grew at an
annual rate of 8.2 percent in Guangdong, while the GDP increased
by 14.2 percent, sales revenue by 17.9 percent and wages by 15.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
The price reform has also helped end the supply shortage which
has long dogged the whole country. According to the State
Administration of Internal Trade, in the first half of this year
there was an adequate supply of more than 600 varieties of major
commodities and in some instances there were excesses.
</P>
<P>
"To an extent, the success of China's economic reform lies in
the success of price reform," experts have said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0374 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
