<HEADLINE> Vieira Fined for His V-Sign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 14 (Xinhua) -- English Premier League club
Arsenal midfielder Patrick Vieira has been found 20,000 pounds
for gesturing at fans following a stormy game at Sheffield
Wednesday in September.
</P>
<P>
The French international was found guilty of misconduct by a
Football Association disciplinary panel, following a hearing in
Birmingham but no suspension was imposed.
</P>
<P>
He was also warned about his future conduct but was cleared of
an alleged assault on a police officer in the players' tunnel.
</P>
<P>
"It's important for us that Patrick escaped suspension. He's
only just come back from injury and it would be a real body blow
if he had gone out of the side again," said Arsenal manager
Arsene Wenger.
</P>
<P>
FA spokesman Steve Double said: "Vieira admitted to the
commission that he made the V-sign in response to racial abuse
from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
"As he went down the tunnel he felt himself grabbed from
behind by an unknown assailant. He said he had broken free
without realising it was a police officer.
</P>
<P>
"The commission heard supporting evidence from club officials,
including Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger. The commission ruled
that Vieira was guilty of misconduct in relation to the gestures
to the crowd, but not guilty in relation to any alleged assault
against a police officer."
</P>
<P>
Vieira was fined 3,000 pounds in July after a confrontation
with West Ham's Ian Pearce after an FA Cup replay four months
earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
