<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Bumper Harvest in 1998: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 15 (Xinhua) -- Despite this summer's
disastrously heavy floods, China expects its 1998 grain output to
have reached the second highest yield ever, almost on a par with
the record results of 1996, according to Wan Baorui, vice-minister
of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Wan announced Monday that China's total grain output will have
surpassed the year's target of 492.5 billion kilograms.
</P>
<P>
He released the figure in his annual report on the country's
agricultural situation during an inspection meeting by the
deputies of the National People's Congress in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
He said that thanks to the Party's basic policies being
implemented in rural areas, farmers have been able to stabilize
their planting and maintained a forward momentum in the
development of agriculture and the rural economy.
</P>
<P>
However, Wan did reveal that grain output in the badly
flood-stricken areas around the Yangtze, Songhua and Nenjiang
rivers was affected, but that output in other regions has either
stabilized or even increased.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that although cotton output this year fell by
300,000 tons, it was still enough to meet the market demands.
</P>
<P>
Edible oil and sugar production are estimated to have grown by
500,000 tons and four million tons respectively; meat and egg
output risen by four and three percent respectively over the the
previous year; and aquatic products are expected to reach a level
of 38 million tons.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the first 10 months of the year, the added
value of township enterprises reached 1,732.5 billion yuan, an
increase of 16.9 percent over the same period last year. The value
of export-oriented products amounted to 520.6 billion yuan, a rise
of 10.7 percent over last year.
</P>
<P>
Wan also revealed that more than 70 percent of villages have
extended the term of farmland contracts with farmers and in
general terms the burden on rural communities has been much
relieved compared to 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
