Cochetel, the head of the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) office in North Ossetia, Russia.
</P>
<P>
Annan "is immediately to hear of the overnight release"
of the U.N. officials," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that "The Secretary-General, who had met
with members of the Cochetel family in Paris four days ago and
then spoke with Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, called
him early Saturday to thank him for his efforts in obtaining the
release."
</P>
<P>
The release came shortly after four foreign hostages, four
engineers working for a British telephone company in Chechnya,
Russia, were abducted and later beheaded.
</P>
<P>
Cochetel, a Frenchman, was abducted on January 29 from his
residence in Vladiskavkaz, capital of North Ossetia near
Chechnya, where hostage-taking has become common.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR said that Cochetel was released during the night of
December 11-12 and that he was exhausted, but in good spirits.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General also echoes the high commissioner for
refugees, Sadako Ogata, in her appeal for the world to remain
focused on the enormous risks humanitarian workers face daily in
their work around the globe," the statement added.  
</P>
