<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Faces EU Court Action Over Environmental Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Brussels, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
decided to make an application to the European Court of Justice
against Britain for its failure to adopt legislation covering
Gibraltar in respect of a number of EU environmental directives.
</P>
<P>
European Commission announced this case here on Monday, which
shows Britain should implement directives in Gibraltar. For some
time, there has been a significant backlog of such directives
awaiting implementing legislation in respect of the territory,
said the commission, the EU's executive body.
</P>
<P>
Though Britain has made some progress recently in clearing the
backlog, its legislation is still lacking for several directives,
one of which, Directive 94/67/EEC, is on the incineration of
hazardous waste.
</P>
<P>
The commission said the directive's objective is to ensure that
specified measures and procedure are in place to prevent or reduce
as far as possible negative environmental effects arising from
hazardous waste incineration. The directive addresses the
pollution of air, soil, surface and groundwater and risks to human
health, and aims to achieve a high level of environmental
protection.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, Britain has sent a draft legislation on this
regard, but has not yet sent any adopted legislation, the
commission said while pointing out that the major EU island member
has also not implemented the other three EU directives, which
reflect the 15-nation bloc's concerns about air traffic noise.
</P>
<P>
The EU commission considers it important that all directives
are implemented in time and throughout the territory where they
are applicable.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
