<HEADLINE> UK Output Prices Hit Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The prices of UK manufactured
goods leaving factory gates have fallen by a record amount which
highlights the difficulties facing the industry.
</P>
<P>
The year-on-year figures for November published by the Office
for National Statistics showed prices producers obtained for their
goods fell by 0.5 percent, the biggest fall since records began in
1958.
</P>
<P>
However, economists said the figures suggest UK inflation
remains subdued, which could lead to further cuts in the cost of
borrowing to stimulate the economy.
</P>
<P>
"This type of data does tend to confirm the wisdom of the
acceleration of rate cuts by the Monetary Policy Committee," said
James Stewart at Weavering Capital.
</P>
<P>
"It's hard to see any upside pressures to inflation. Given the
inflation and output data we have seen I would not be surprised at
all to see at least a 50 basis point cut in January," he added.
</P>
<P>
The MPC slashed rates by 50 basis points last week to 6.25
percent, bringing the total amount of easing to 125 basis points
since October. 
</P>
