<BODY>
<HEADLINE> There Is Not Much for U.N. to Do in Angola, Annan Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 14 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said on Monday the United Nations could not do much in
Angola, where a civil war has resumed in recent months, and the
Security Council would soon have to decide whether the world body
still had a role to play in the African country.
</P>
<P>
"There is a war. The United Nations can't do much because we
don't have many people in the field," Annan told a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to a 1,000-member U.N. observer mission that
has been trying unsuccessfully to halt the unravelling of a 1994
agreement aimed at ending nearly two decades of conflict between
the Angolan government and the rebel UNITA.
</P>
<P>
In the early days of the peace process, the U.N. troop presence
numbered more than 7,000.
</P>
<P>
"We have to regroup our peacekeeping forces for the purpose of
their own security," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council soon will be obliged to decide whether
the U.N. has a role to play or not. If we cannot retain contact
with all parties, can we really play a role?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
There had been no direct contact with UNITA leader Jonas
Savimbi, "So we really have to give a comprehensive review of what
is occurring in Angola and our position there," the U.N. chief
said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council earlier this month renewed the mandate of
the U.N. Observer Mission in Angola, known as MONUA, until
February 26, 1999. It said it would continue to adjust the
deployment and structure of the force in accordance with security
conditions and its ability to carry out its mandate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
