<HEADLINE> Tsohatzopoulos, Holbrooke Hold Talks on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 14 (Xinhua) -- Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos Monday held talks with visiting U.S. presidential
envoy on Cyprus, Richard Holbrooke, on ways of breaking the
impasse of the protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after their talks, Tsohatzopoulos said that the result
of the talks was "a difficult issue to pin down," according to the
semi- official Athens News Agency (ANA).
</P>
<P>
He added that both sides elaborated on the prospects that each
side saw as realistic.
</P>
<P>
U.S. ambassador to Greece Nicholas Burns, who also attended the
talks, described the meeting as "excellent and useful."
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke, along with U.S. State Department coordinator for
Cyprus Thomas Miller, is now having a working dinner with Greek
Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos and they are expected to
discuss Greek-Turkish relations and Cyprus, especially U.S.
efforts to avoid a crisis by finding a way for Nicosia to cancel
its planned installation of Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft
missiles.
</P>
<P>
To strengthen its defense capacity, Cyprus decided earlier last
year to purchase the Russian missiles, but U.S. and some European
countries have opposed the deployment of the missiles, saying that
this would increase the tension on the divided island republic.
Turkey also openly threatened to use force to prevent the missile
deployment.
</P>
<P>
While insisting that the missiles will be deployed as planned,
the Cyprus government has expressed the willingness to postpone
the missile deployment only if there is substantive progress on
Nicosia's proposal to demilitarize Cyprus and if there is a
resumption of U.N. sponsored talks for the island's reunification.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
