<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0397 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New EU Members Strengthen Environment Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Brussels, December 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
Monday expressed here its views that the accession of Austria,
Finland and Sweden to the integration bloc has resulted in
strengthened EU environment protection standards.
</P>
<P>
In its newly adopted Communication, a kind of shaped policy
document, the European Commission said when the three countries
joined the EU on January 1, 1995, a special provision allowed them
to keep certain different national health and environment
provisions for four years. The period of the provision, the Review
Clause in the Act of Accession, will end on December 31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
During this period, the EU reviewed its own health and
environmental standards accordingly, in close cooperation with the
three new members. The Communication said in almost all cases, the
review process resulted in the adoption of strengthened
environmental standards throughout the EU, for example on sulphur
in petrol, mercury in batteries and labelling of dangerous
substances.
</P>
<P>
Following the adoption of the Communication, EU Environment
Commissioner Ritt Bjerregaard said: "The review process
demonstrates that the EU has been able to ensure a high level of
environmental protection and health standards for the citizens in
Ausria, Finland and Sweden."
</P>
<P>
The commission said that in the accession negotiations with the
three countries, the environment and health were important and
sensitive issues due to their high level of protection in these
states.
</P>
<P>
A survey shows that the review proved to be a success in
protecting the environment and human health, according to the
European Commission.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
