<DOCNO> XIE19981215.0398 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Londoners to Elect Mayor in May, 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LONDON, December 14 (Xinhua) -- British government announced on
Monday that Londoners will elect their first Mayor on May 4, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister John Prescott said elections for a
25-member Greater London Authority, which would supervise the
Mayor's activities and be required to approve his budgets, would
take place on the same day.
</P>
<P>
Prescott told the Parliament the Mayor would have "real powers
and responsibilities."
</P>
<P>
Functions would include coordinating London's transport
system, including its huge underground railway network, making
major decisions on planning, and helping to tackle the city's
environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
London has been without a city-wide authority since 1986
when a Conservative government under Margaret Thatcher abolished
the Greater London Council (GLC), which at that time had a
reputation as a hotbed of radical socialism.
</P>
<P>
The new Mayor and Authority will mark a third step towards
devolution of power from central government since the Labor
government came to office last year.
</P>
<P>
Bills to set up separate parliaments for Scotland and Wales
have already been passed and elections for the two bodies are
due to take place next May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
